<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Horowitz     05-07 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Horowitz,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Art Deco Pioneer Dies Of Complications From AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrial designer Leonard Horowitz,
whose eye for color helped transform this city's Art Deco District
into a rainbow of pastel colors and renovated beachfront hotels,
died of complications from AIDS. He was 43.
   Horowitz, who died Friday, saw the potential of buildings that
had weathered through the years when few others could.
   Up to 150 Art Deco buildings in Miami Beach are painted pink,
purple, peach and periwinkle, and about half are Horowitz' designs.
   He founded the Miami Design Preservation League with Barbara
Capitman in 1976. ``Really, he taught me what I know about Art
Deco,'' said Ms. Capitman.
   In 1980, much of the Art Deco District's buildings displayed
weathered, cracked stucco. But Horowitz could see past the peeling
paint, and came up with a scheme for a whole block of buildings
that made them look like confections. The idea caught on.
   Horowitz was born in New York City, and grew up with visions of
the Art Deco-style Radio City Music Hall.
   He started a design firm in New York, but moved to Miami Beach.
He continued doing interior design as well as the Deco district's
colorful exteriors.
   It was not immediately known if Horowitz left survivors. Plans
for a memorial service were pending.
</TEXT>
