<FIRST>r a AM-BargeBlast 1stLd-Writethru a0609 05-07 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barge Blast, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0609,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Empty Barge Explodes on Ohio River: One Missing, Two Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to UPDATE that one man missing sted dead; SUBS
grafs 8-10, `The identity ... blast occurred' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
details of blast, plan to drag river for missing man; picks up last graf,
`None of ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST LIVERPOOL, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chemical fumes sparked an explosion
in a barge docked for cleaning at this Ohio River town Saturday,
igniting a fire that injured two men and left one missing.
   The barge was empty but apparently contained residues from its
usual cargo of benzene, a flammable chemical solvent, police said.
   Residents within a half-mile of the 3:30 p.m. blaze were asked
to close their windows late Saturday afternoon and evening to avoid
breathing possibly hazardous fumes, said East Liverpool police
Officer Virgil Williams.
   Benzene may produce irritating or toxic gases when burned.
Vapors from the chemical also can cause coughing and lung
irritation, as well as dizziness.
   Williams said the barge had been docked between the Ohio River
and some railroad tracks for cleaning. East Liverpool is in eastern
Ohio.
   ``They were cleaning the barge,'' he said. ``It was empty and
fumes apparently ignited.''
   The blaze was extinguished by the town's Fire Department about
two hours after it began, he said. Firefighters remained at the
scene Saturday evening, wetting down ashes.
   Rescue crews planned to drag the 40-foot-deep river Sunday in
search of the missing man, who disappeared when the blast blew the
hatch off the vessel, said city police Capt. Fred Hyder.
   The two injured men were taken to East Liverpool City Hospital,
where one, Mike Newbrough of Chester, W. Va., was listed in serious
condition with burns, a concussion and fractures, said a nursing
supervisor who refused to identify herself.
   The other victim, Richard Stanley of East Liverpool, also
suffered burns but refused treatment and left the hospital, she
said.
   Hyder said the three men were on the barge looking down into the
hatch when it exploded.
   None of the chemical spilled into the river, Williams said.
</TEXT>
