<FIRST>r a AM-GasSpill     05-07 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gas Spill,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barge Spills 80,000 Gallons of Gasoline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CATSKILL, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barge carrying over 2 million gallons of
gasoline struck a buoy Saturday and spilled about 80,000 gallons
into the rain-swollen Hudson River, environmental officials said.
   The leak aboard the Bouchard 45 was stopped and Coast Guard
officials were investigating the cause of the accident, the state
Department of Environmental Conservation said.
   The accident about 30 miles south of Albany was reported about 4
a.m., said DEC regional director Jane Magee. The barge continued
upriver to Ravena after the accident, where workers pumped out some
compartments of the craft and shifted gasoline to other parts of
the barge, she said.
   Getty Oil owns the gasoline, Coast Guard officials said.
   Once the gasoline was shifted, Magee said, the barge was to
continue on to Rensselaer and unload, then return to New York City
for repairs.
   Rain and wind broke up most of the gasoline by Saturday
afternoon, she said. A contractor was hired to clean up the rest of
the spill, Coast Guard officials said.
   ``We're expecting it will have a minimum impact and are
arranging to get some biologists on the river,'' Magee said.
</TEXT>
