<FIRST>r a AM-ZapII 2ndLd-Writethru a0600 05-07 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zap II, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0600,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zap Hosts Reunion Of College Spring Fling That Ended In A Riot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8, `Saturday's reunion ... Kessler said' with 2
grafs to UPDATE with bigger crowd estimate, 30 arrests; picks up 9th graf,
`The mood ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZAP, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only about 50 leather-clad motorcyclists and a
few hundred other peaceable partyers zipped into Zap on Saturday
for the anniversary of the ``Zip to Zap'' party that ended in a
riot 20 years ago.
   ``That makes my day. I love people and I love things happening.
We do have it in order, so I am not worried,'' said Mayor Albert
Sailer said, smiling and waving beneath his blue baseball cap,
which was emblazoned with the slogan ``I Zipped To Zap And Had A
Blast.''
   ``This isn't anything like it was 20 years ago,'' said Mercer
County Sheriff Ron Kessler, who was among the police who tried to
quell the original riot. ``It was a long evening then.''
   Sailer had been told to expect 500 bikers for Zip To Zap II,
which was originally planned as 12 hours of partying and rock music
in one of North Dakota's smaller towns.
   In 1969, this quiet hamlet of 300 people about 90 miles
northwest of Bismarck hosted the first Zip to Zap, an idea hatched
by the editor of the student newspaper at North Dakota State
University.
   It ended in disaster. The National Guard was called in to chase
2,000 drunken revelers out of town. Celebrants set a bonfire in
Main Street and caused about $3,000 in damage before the crowd was
dispersed.
   Saturday's reunion started quietly but livened up as the sun
went down. People began dancing in the street to the blare of
recorded music, and Zap's two bars were jammed. Kessler said the
crowd swelled to more than 500 people.
   Thirty people had been arrested by late Saturday night, mostly
for being too young to drink or for drinking on public property.
Middle-aged people and more than a few locals mingled with the
student crowd.
   The mood was festive, far from a mob scene. There were guest
books for people to sign. Soda pop and hot dogs were for sale
everywhere, although beer was banned in the streets.
   D.J. Guerrero of Fargo, who attended the first Zip to Zap in
1969, remembered that beer prices helped touch off the riot.
   ``It was a mass of humanity out on the streets and everybody was
having a good time, a good time gone sour,'' he said. ``Townspeople
started jacking up the prices on beer and food and everything and
kids got upset. They doubled the price on six-packs of beer.''
   Guerrero, 53, brought his wife and two children to Zap for the
reunion.``They wanted to zip to Zap, so I said OK,'' he said.
   Guerrero was also making amends for what happened in 1969. ``I
apologized to the people here for what happened. The National Guard
... had to save the town. There would have been nothing left here.''
   Alda Peterson transformed her garage just off Main Street into a
mini-cafe, complete with $9 souvenir T-shirts: ``Zip To Zap. We're
Back.''
   The reunion was a good idea, the 64-year-old woman said. ``You
have to let the kids do something, and the older people are just as
nosy.''
   Her son called her from California Friday night, asking if she
was ready for the ``zippers'' and envious that he could not be
home, Mrs. Peterson said.
   ``If everything is kept under control, it would be nice to be an
annual event,'' she said.
   But the denizens of Zap are far from agreement on that idea.
Some wanted the town barricaded Saturday to keep the visitors out,
she said. ``It's a touchy question,'' she said.
</TEXT>
