<FIRST>r a AM-RadioactiveContainer 1stLd-Writethru a0616 05-07 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Radioactive Container, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0616,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eighty-Eight Passengers, Eight Crew Members To Be Checked For Radiation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers and crew on a Mexicana Airlines
plane that had recently dropped off leaking packages of a
radioactive chemical showed no sign of radiation contamination,
officials said Sunday.
   Officials said earlier that an undetermined amount of
molypentachloride, a corrosive that emits low-level beta radiation,
was found in the cargo hold of the plane. Flight 820 landed at
about 10:20 p.m. Saturday.
   But fire communications supervisor Charles Maier said checks
showed the plane wasn't contaminated, nor were the 88 passengers or
eight crew members aboard Flight 820. The plane landed here at
about 10:20 p.m. Saturday.
   Two or three packages of the radioactive material were loaded on
the Boeing 727 at Chicago's O'Hare International Airport for a
previous flight to Mexico, said Sue Gagner, a U.S. Nuclear
Regulatory Commission spokeswoman in Washington.
   The packages were unloaded in Mexico and were found to be
leaking while the plane was en route from Acapulco to Philadelphia,
according to the NRC and police.
   While in flight, the pilot of the airliner radioed to Mexicana
Airlines officials about the leak and airline officials contacted
Philadelphia police, police Cpl. Andrew Chowmentowski said.
</TEXT>
