<FIRST>u i AM-NorthernIreland 3rdLd-Writethru a0623 05-07 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0623,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Bombs Injure Nine Soldiers</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 3 grafs to CLARIFY that explosions occurred overnight
Saturday. Pickup 4th graf `They said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs exploded near British
patrols overnight, injuring nine soldiers, police said Sunday.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility for the first
attack, saying it marked Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's 10
years in power. There was no immediate claim of responsibility for
the other explosion.
   In the first bombing, police said the soldiers were in a mobile
patrol at Moybane, near Crossmaglen, close to the south Armagh
border with the Irish Republic on Saturday night when the bomb
exploded in an abandoned house.
   They said one of the five men was seriously hurt by being hurled
through the air with flying debris, and the house was wrecked.
   The five soldiers were airlifted by helicopter to a hospital,
and the area was sealed off to await inspection by daylight in case
of booby traps, police said.
   The IRA said in a statement that it carried out the bombing to
mark Mrs. Thatcher's 10th year in power. On the actual anniversary
on Thursday it said it set off a roadside bomb that day in
Silverbridge near Crossmaglen that kiled one soldier and wounded
three others.
   The second bomb exploded several hours later on Sunday, 12 miles
away at Camlough, County Down, as another mobile patrol was
passing. One soldier was sent to a hospital for treatment and three
others were given first aid, police said.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
unite the mainly Protestant province with the overwhelmingly Roman
Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
