<FIRST>u i AM-Takeshita     05-07 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Takeshita,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Prime Minister Ends Southeast Asian Tour, Hints At His Replacement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita ended his five-nation Southeast Asian tour Sunday and
headed back to Japan to annoint a successor and restore his party's
scandal-ridden image.
   Japan's Kyodo News Service, in a report from the Philippine
capital, said Takeshita hinted he would ask veteran politician
Masayoshi Ito to accept the premiership despite his reluctance to
take the post.
   President Corazon Aquino and other senior Filipino officials
were on hand for a 10-minute farewell ceremony at Manila airport,
where Takeshita received a 19-gun salute before boarding the plane
for Tokyo. There were no speeches.
   Takeshita went ahead with the visit despite his announcement
April 25 that he would resign to take responsibility for a scandal
in which the Recruit Co. is accused of seeking to buy influence
with political donations or stock transactions that yielded huge
profits to politicians, bureaucrats and others.
   On Monday, Takeshita is expected to meet with Ito, a former
foreign minister. Japanese sources say Ito is expected eventually
to accept the appointment if certain conditions are met, though
these are unclear.
   Japan's Kyodo News Service reported Sunday that Takeshita hinted
to Japanese reporters traveling with with him that he would ask Ito
to take the job.
   Kyodo said Takeshita stopped short of mentioning Ito by name but
said ``it is quite natural for a respectable man to win the heart
of the people.''
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party has focused on Ito as a
successor because so many of the party's leaders are tainted by
Recruit donations or stock deals, while Ito as seen as basically
clean.
   But the 75-year-old Ito, chairman of the party's policy-making
Executive Council, has cited his age and heart problems caused by
diabetes as reasons for declining the nomination to be party
president and thus prime minister.
   During his trip, Takeshita also visited Indonesia, Thailand,
Malaysia and Singapore. All five countries he toured are members of
the non-communist Association of Southeast Asian Nations, the major
regional trading bloc.
</TEXT>
