<FIRST>u i BC-Iran-Refinery     05-07 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Iran-Refinery,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abadan Refinery, Once World's Largest, Resumes Exports After 8-Year
Gap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's Abadan oil refinery, once the
world's largest, resumed exports Saturday after an eight-year gap,
the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said a 10,000-ton shipment of
fuel oil from the refinery left Bandar Mahshahr port, but did not
say where it was headed.
   The refinery, located only a few miles from the border with
Iraq, shut down soon after the Iran-Iraq war broke out in September
1980.
   The 3,200-acre complex was heavily shelled by Iraqi artillery
during the war. More than 150 personnel were killed and lost
production was estimated at $9 billion.
   Around 6,000 technicians and specialists started round-the-clock
repair work immediately after a United Nations-sponsored cease-fire
halted the gulf war Aug. 20.
   Production resumed April 1 with an initial capacity of 130,000
barrels a day of oil products, IRNA said.
   Capacity is expected to rise later this year and reach 360,000
barrels a day in the next two to three years. Before the war, the
refinery produced 650,000 barrels a day.
   Following repairs of war damage at Iran's six other refineries,
the country's total refinery capacity is currently estimated at
850,000 barrels a day.
</TEXT>
