<SECOND>BC-Earthquake,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mile Earthquake Shakes California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake jolted Southern California
Saturday night, but there were no immediate reports of injury or
property damage, authorities said.
   The quake struck at 11:07 p.m. and measured 3.7 on the Richter
scale of ground motion, said Robert O'Rourke, spokesman for the
California Institute of Technology in Pasadena. The temblor was
centered one mile northwest of Brea.
   Telephone banks at the Orange County Sheriff's Department lit up
with calls following the jolt, said Deputy R. Nink.
   ``Everybody said they were feeling it shake a little bit,'' Nink
said. ``We've had maybe 10 or 15 calls. It wasn't anything huge,
but I guess it shook some people up.''
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage.
