<FIRST>r i BC-Britain-Missiles     05-07 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Missiles,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report British Boycott Threat To European Missile Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported Sunday that the British
government will refuse to negotiate with the Soviet Union on
reducing short-range nuclear missiles in Europe even if the other
15 members of NATO agree to do so.
   The Sunday Telegraph, in a Washington-dated story, said Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher made her views known to President Bush
in diplomatic notes and telephone conversations last week.
   ``Her tough stance on the issue is proving the main obstacle in
the Bush administration's frantic search for a compromise after
West Germany's insistence that negotiations must take place as soon
as possible,'' the newspaper reported.
   It said Mrs. Thatcher called Bush after failing to agree on a
united NATO policy at her meeting with West German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl on April 30.
   At that meeting in West Germany, Mrs. Thatcher failed to
persuade Kohl to abandon his quest for early talks with Moscow on
reducing the missiles. The British leader argued that the 88 Lance
missiles should be modernized, not removed, and that their
reduction or removal would put Europe in greater danger of sudden
nuclear war involving strategic nuclear missiles.
   The Sunday Telegraph said Britain and the United States want to
update the Lance because of Soviet modernization of short-range
nuclear armory and Soviet superiority in conventional and chemical
weapons.
