<FIRST>r a BC-SpaceShuttle     05-07 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Space Shuttle,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantis Streaks Around Earth, Magellan Continues Voyage to Venus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlantis' five astronauts awoke to
music from the movie ``Rocky'' on Sunday, the final full day of
their shuttle mission in which they deployed a planetary probe now
bound for Venus.
   The Magellan probe continued on its 15-month voyage to Venus at
a rate of about 6,500 mph. The spacecraft, launched from the
shuttle's cargo bay Thursday night, already had traveled more than
430,000 miles by early Sunday morning.
   Later Sunday, shuttle commander David Walker and pilot Ronald
Grabe planned to run through a series of tests to make sure the
shuttle's computers and control jets are ready for the fiery plunge
through the Earth's atmosphere on Monday.
   Atlantis, which blasted away from Kennedy Space Center on
Thursday, is scheduled to end its four-day mission with a landing
at Edwards Air Force Base, Calif., at 12:43 p.m. California time.
   Also Sunday, the astronauts planned to try to photograph
lightning strikes at night and work on a metals processing
experiment as well as pack their belongings in preparation for the
return home.
   The workload on the four-day flight has been limited because the
Magellan probe and its rocket booster, which together weighed
45,000 pounds, did not allow for many experiments to be carried
aboard.
