<HEAD>Chemical Leak Kills Crewman Aboard Ship In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crewman was killed and two of his companions were
hospitalized after inhaling a gas aboard a Panamanian tanker at
Shimotsu port in western Japan, the Maritime Safety Agency said
Sunday.
   The agency, Japan's coast guard, said the South Korean sailor
who died, Chon In-su, 39, entered a hold aboard the ship Saturday
night to measure what he thought were residual amounts of benzene.
   When he fell to the floor, a colleague, Ok Nam-suk, 52, put on a
mask and went to help, but he also collapsed, the agency said. A
third sailor, Yun Won-sup, 23, rescued Ok but became ill before he
could bring out Chon.
   Japanese rescuers brought out Chon 30 minutes later, but he died.
   The agency was investigating the cause of the accident aboard
the 687-ton Modern Marine, which arrived Saturday with a cargo of
benzene from China.
