<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-89 1139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-NewCaledonia     05-07 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Caledonia,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Premier Revives Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French Premier Michel Rocard on
Sunday said elections in this territory will proceed as planned,
reversing an earlier decision to cancel them because of the
slayings of two independence leaders.
   Rocard was among an estimated 5,000 people who attended the
funerals Sunday of Jean-Marie Tjibaou, leader of the Kanak
Socialist National Liberation Front, and Tjibaou's top assistant,
Yeiwene Yeiwene.
   The two were shot and killed on the island of Ouvea on Thursday
by Djubelly Wea, a hard-line separatist opposed to Tjibaou's
moderate policies. Wea was killed by Tjibaou's bodyguards after the
attack.
   Andre Tangopi, another hard-line separatist, was charged in both
shooting deaths but police did not say what role he played in the
attack. He was wounded in an exchange of gunfire that followed the
assassinations and was hospitalized under police guard in Noumea,
the provincial capital.
   Rocard on Friday had postponed the elections in the restive
territory after the slayings. On Sunday, he said they would proceed
as planned June 11.
   ``A criminal doesn't stop the course of peace in progress,'' the
premier said. ``Tolerance will not abdicate in the face of
fanaticism.''
   Last year, Tjibaou abandoned demands for immediate independence
in the territory and signed an agreement in Paris for a peace
process that would end in 1998 with a referendum on independence.
   Many of Tjibaou's followers were unhappy with the accord, which
was aimed at ending three years of sporadic separatist violence
here.
   Tjibaou and Yeiwene had gone to Ouvea to take part in ceremonies
marking the first anniversary of the assault by French police on a
cave where separatists were holding more than 20 other French
officers hostage. The fighting left 19 separatists and two
policemen dead.
   Native Melanesians, known as Kanaks, make up 43 percent of the
inhabitants of New Caledonia, an archipelago 1,000 miles off the
coast of Australia. Most Kanaks favor independence. European
settlers and their descendants make up 37 percent of the population
and most want to remain French.
   The rest of the population is Polynesians and Asians, most of
whom also favor remaining French.
</TEXT>
