<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-89 1140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     05-07 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Newspaper Welcomes Plan to Include Blacks in Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Arica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's largest black
newspaper Sunday welcomed a Cabinet minister's proposal to include
blacks in Parliament, saying the government ``has finally seen the
light.''
   City Press described a speech in Parliament last week by
Constitutional Development Minister Chris Heunis as ``possibly the
most significant policy statement'' ever by a senior government
official.
   Heunis, however, made clear that the governing National Party
would oppose any system in which white interests could be overruled.
   Heunis, outlining the National Party's latest constitutional
strategy, said the black majority should have a role in the
Cabinet, in Parliament and in the election of a president. He said
the government might allow South Africans to participate in
political structures that transcend racial lines.
   ``Strange but true,'' said a City Press editorial. ``The
government has finally seen the light _ realizing the need to
establish an authentic Parliament that will represent all South
African communities.''
   South Africa's 28 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. Parliament has chambers for Asians and people of
mixed-race, but the constitution gives almost total power to the
party that wins the most votes among the 5 million whites.
   Militant anti-apartheid leaders, committed to the concept of
one-person, one-vote, have ignored Heunis' speech. But mainstream
white newspapers Sunday joined City Press in depicting it as a
milestone.
   The Sunday Times, the country's largest-selling newspaper,
described the speech as a ``dramatic U-turn'' and ``one of the most
important policy shifts of the past decade.''
   ``The government has accepted that South Africans be allowed to
choose their own political and social groupings, irrespective of
race,'' said The Sunday Times. ``The stand contradicts South
Africa's classical apartheid dogma which holds that all South
Africans must exercise their political and social rights through
the group to which they belong.''
   Rapport, a pro-government, Afrikaans newspaper, ran a front-page
banner headline saying: ``Now: One Parliament.'' The accompanying
article evoked the image of ``a united South Africa where all _
white, black, brown and Indian _ can be represented in one Cabinet
and one Parliament.''
   John MacLennon, a political writer for the Argus newspaper
group, said Heunis' speech suggested the National Party would
forsake the votes of far-right whites during the campaign leading
to general elections Sept. 6. He said the Nationalists will adopt a
pro-reform platform aimed at whites who favor change but not
majority rule.
   The far-right Conservative Party said Heunis' plan would lead
swiftly to black domination.
   The anti-apartheid Democratic Party, which hopes to replace the
Conservatives as the largest white opposition faction in
Parliament, called Heunis' speech promising but questioned whether
the rhetoric could be converted into law.
   City Press also expressed caution, saying blacks ``have been let
down time and time again by people who make promises and never live
up to them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890507-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-89 1137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-EnergyPolicy Bjt   05-07 0949</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Energy Policy, Bjt,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuclear Power Taking Key Role In Bush Energy Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nuclear power, new technologies and a closer
eye on the environment are emerging as key elements of what a
senior Energy Department official says will be ``the first real
national energy policy this country has ever had.''
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins has told Congress he'll have
an energy plan ready by next April, although there are indications
this target may be missed.
   Watkins and his chief deputy, Henson Moore, have appeared before
several key industry groups recently to sketch in some of the key
contours of what Watkins says will be a ``common sense approach''
to putting America on a more solid energy foundation.
   Some of the main areas of emphasis will be familiar: greater
leeway for oil companies to explore on federal lands, tax breaks
for oil drillers, decontrol of natural gas prices, expansion of
nuclear power and pursuit of basic research.
   More novel will be the Energy Department's pursuit of what
Watkins calls ``technology transfer'' _ ensuring that energy
research advances made in the department's national scientific
laboratories are made available to industry and universities. The
labs' main focus is on top-secret nuclear weapons programs, but
Watkins said they have done extensive work in unclassified energy
areas.
   Watkins also has said his energy strategy will be more
comprehensive than anything produced during the Reagan
administration. It will take into account, for example, the links
between energy and the environment, including acid rain and the
global atmospheric warming trend caused mainly by burning of fossil
fuels, he said.
   Moore has billed the evolving strategy as a clear departure from
past policies.
   ``We're going to fashion the first real national energy policy
this country has ever had,'' the former Louisiana congressman said
at his swearing-in ceremony April 20.
   The government has produced many energy policies in the past,
but Moore's remark seemed to reflect the fact that the Reagan
administration's policy suffered from criticism by
environmentalists and a lack of interest by the general public.
   ``You could ask 100 people if the country had an energy policy
and 99 would say `no,''' Donald Hodel, the energy secretary from
1982-85, said in a telephone interview. He said there was a policy
but that it was not commonly recognized.
   Watkins, an engineer by training and a career naval officer,
wants to broaden the scope of the government's energy involvement.
Beyond the traditional issues of energy production, price and
supply, Watkins sees room for his department to help stimulate
young people's interest in science, math and engineering _ areas of
education that he says are vital to the nation's energy future.
   This is where the nuclear issue fits in. Watkins is a devoted
supporter of commercial nuclear power, and he is troubled at the
depth of public distrust of this energy source, which accounts for
nearly one-fifth of all electricity generation.
   No orders for new nuclear plants have been placed in 11 years
and none are expected for the rest of the century. Scores of plants
have been cancelled in the past decade, and nuclear's share of
energy production is projected to fall in the 1990s. The Reagan
administration supported nuclear power but failed to revive it.
   This has produced two results that Watkins says threaten the
nation's long-term energy security: a shrinking energy base and a
deterioration of nuclear expertise.
   This is part of Watkins' motivation for launching a publicity
campaign against New York Gov. Mario Cuomo's plan to tear down the
Shoreham nuclear plant on Long Island, which earlier this month was
cleared for startup by federal regulators.
   ``Because Shoreham is the right energy source at the right time
for the right place, its operation should stand as a symbol of the
promise and potential of nuclear power in America,'' Watkins said
after the plant got its license.
   Cuomo wants to tear it down because of doubts about whether Long
Islanders could safety evacuate in the event of an accident.
Watkins has vowed to fight the dismantlement.
   Watkins is taking an analogous approach to the problem of a
slumping oil industry, whose prospects for long-term revival have
been damaged by the Exxon Valdez oil spill. As a result of that
accident _ the biggest spill in U.S. history _ industry hopes for
expanding exploration on the North Slope have diminished.
   Watkins has expressed alarm at the decline in U.S. oil
production since 1986, which has coincided with a rise in oil use
and a resulting jump in oil imports.
   Besides making the country more reliable on oil from the Middle
East, the domestic oil slump has weakened young people's interest
in learning the business, he said. Watkins recently cited figures
showing that between 1982 and 1987 the number of freshmen enrolled
in petroleum engineering schools plunged from 3,300 to 271.
   ``Let us at least be forward thinking enough to prepare
America's young people to be part of the energy breakthroughs of
the next century,'' Watkins said.
   The technological advances that Watkins thinks are most
important include:
   _A ``clean coal'' method of burning the nation's most abundant
energy source in ways that provide more power with less pollution.
The department plans to spend $5 billion through 1992 on
demonstration projects by private companies.
   _New designs for nuclear reactors to reduce their vulnerability
to meltdowns or other serious accidents that have eroded public
confidence in the industry. Numerous such ``passively safe''
designs are under development.
   _A superconducting super collider. Watkins says he will push for
federal financing of the $5.9 billion physics installation in Texas
at which scientists plan to explore the fundamental components of
matter and energy.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890507-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-89 1144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-JerseyCityElection     05-07 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jersey City Election,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sport Of Politics In Full Swing In Jersey City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 people trudged in out of a
pounding rain one recent night to hoot and holler at the city's
favorite spectator sport.
   Politics.
   ``Politics is like baseball in Jersey City, and it's hardball
all the time,'' said Thomas Mansheim, chairman of the Department of
Urban Studies at St. Peter's College. ``People are interested in
it, they follow it and a lot of times their jobs are dependent on
it, so they really live for it.''
   This year, it's politics as unusual in Jersey City, an
industrial waterfront city of 230,000 that sits a stone's throw
from the Statue of Liberty on the western shore of New York Harbor.
   A record 10 candidates are running for mayor in Tuesday's
free-for-all. If no candidate receives more than 50 percent of the
vote, the top two finishers will spend another month hurling
epithets until a June 13 runoff.
   The election is non-partisan, but a registered Democrat likely
will win since Democrats have outnumbered Republicans as long as
anyone can remember. Today the ratio is 13-to-1.
   The lineup of candidates includes the incumbent, two former
mayors, four city councilmen, a banker, a police officer and an
insurance broker.
   Decorum is not their best quality.
   Lofty promises of political reform are met with sarcasm, often
sparking hearty guffaws from voters. And biting attacks abound
among the candidates.
   In campaign advertisements, one candidate refers to his
opponents as ``political hacks.'' Another says he's fighting ``The
Corrupt Political Machine.''
   Based on each camp's estimates, more than $3 million will be
spent to capture the $65,000-a-year job. Jersey City's mayor
influences spending of about $400 million-plus in public funds, and
has final say-so on filling approximately 6,500 city jobs.
   Just last Tuesday, a federal judge took note of the city's
patronage system, blasting incumbent Mayor Anthony Cucci for
running a ``spoils system'' that punished public employees who
didn't support his 1985 election bid.
   ``His attempts to persuade the court that a new breeze blew into
City Hall on July 1, 1985, ... (are) unavailing,'' U.S. District
Judge Harold A. Ackerman said. He ruled that a police officer was
illegally demoted for supporting then-Mayor Gerald McCann instead
of Cucci in 1985.
   ``The air was fetid,'' added Ackerman. ``It was sadly, business
as usual in Jersey City.''
   Battling the party machine and the old-time political bosses has
become the common theme of this year's mayoral fight, as the
candidates go after an electorate changed by an influx of
upper-income executives and minority groups.
   It used to be that candidates only had to reach out to the
Italian and Irish strongholds in the city.
   But as the city changed, so did politics. It is estimated there
are 15,000 people from India, 20,000 Filipinos and 10,000 Egyptians
in the city, although it's unclear how many of those people are
registered voters. An estimated 20,000 Hispanic and 25,000 black
residents are registered to vote.
   For the first time, a black, Council President Glenn Cunningham,
is considered a serious mayoral contender.
   The campaign has stirred all the emotions of a tight baseball
pennent race, which was at no time more apparent than on the rainy
night of the city's first mayoral debate. Four-hundred screaming
supporters crammed into a room at Jersey City Community College to
hear nine of the candidates take potshots at each other.
   Mansheim said he sees Cucci, McCann, Cunningham and two-term
Councilman Thomas Fricchione as the four most likely candidates to
make it to the runoff election.
   The others, he said, are running not to win the mayor's seat,
but to win influence.
   ``That's a major part of the reason for running for mayor,''
Mansheim said. ``Even if they don't have a chance, they'll
negotiate, for jobs mostly. It's not winner-take-all in Jersey City
by a longshot.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890507-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-89 1151EST</FILEID>
