<FIRST>r w AM-PrivateClubs     05-07 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Private Clubs,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private Clubs that Bar Blacks and Women Hamper Judge Nominees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Candidates for federal judge who belong to
discriminatory clubs are finding last-minute resignations may not
be enough to win over critics and save their chances for a seat on
the bench.
   ``Resigning immediately prior to being appointed or knowing that
one may be appointed is not adequate,'' says Sen. Howard M.
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio. ``It misses the point. The concern is that the
jurist is going to be considered open-minded and fair.''
   The Senate _ which makes the final decision on judicial
confirmation _ thus far has not flatly ruled out approval of
nominees who belong to discriminatory clubs, but the pendulum
appears headed that way.
   In practice, consideration of potentially controversial nominees
sometimes simply grinds to a halt without formal, public action.
   One attorney's hopes for a seat on the bench fizzled in 1988
when he waited until two weeks before his scheduled Senate hearing
to resign from Virginia's exclusive James River Club and told a
black group he never felt ``any kind of moral fire within my belly
to go out and correct what is perceived to be wrong by some.''
   A 17-year-veteran of the Colorado Supreme Court saw his hopes
die last year after he balked when lawmakers urged him to resign
from a country club with no black members and specific restrictions
on women. He said he would not bow to political pressure ``to
enhance my chances for confirmation.''
   The new concern about club memberships goes beyond the Senate.
   The American Bar Association last week took steps to revise its
rules and ban judges from being members of clubs that ``invidiously
discriminate.'' It could be the group's official policy by February
1990.
   No one is challenging the right of private clubs to
discriminate, as long as they are truly private and not merely
wearing that label as a means of dodging the public accommodations
laws.
   The question is how much membership in such a club should weigh
as lawmakers consider attorneys for lifetime appointments to the
bench and whether judges who belong to clubs that discriminate can
ever project an image of fairness.
   Metzenbaum says he could support a member of a discriminatory
club for judge if the candidate had consistently worked to change
such policies. But he scoffs at last-minute resignations merely to
appease the Judiciary Committee.
   Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., another Judiciary Committee member,
says, however, that membership in such a club ``shouldn't be the
sole and only reason for knocking the guy down if he's extremely
well qualified.''
   ``It should not be used in the most extraordinary or absurd ways
that it's used sometimes in the Judiciary Committee,'' he says.
``If you like the guy's philosophy and you think he's great, you
don't care what the heck he belongs to.''
   Simpson says the club issue has not been applied evenly and
cites a pending dispute about the nomination of San Francisco
attorney Vaughn Walker for a District Court judgeship in that city.
   Walker, nominated by former President Reagan, stoutly defended
San Francisco's 128-year-old Olympic Club last year and failed to
win approval from the committee. The club had a handful of black
members and bylaw provisions that bar women.
   Walker's nomination was submitted again by President Bush and
Walker resigned from the club in February.
   Simpson notes that Supreme Court Justice Anthony Kennedy was a
member of the same club and resigned a month before his 1987
hearing before the committee. He says the panel was tolerant of
Kennedy's belated resignation ``because he was exceptionally well
qualified.''
   As for Walker, Simpson says, ``They're still ramming it to him.''
   ``The whole transgression of his entire life is that he was a
member of this same sinister club,'' says Simpson. ``I think that's
stupid.''
   Meanwhile, Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., is protesting Walker's
defense of the club in testimony last year.
   ``I have reached the conclusion that his actions with respect to
his membership in a discriminatory club are disqualifying,''
Cranston said in an April 4 letter to Judiciary Committee Chairman
Joseph Biden, D-Del. Cranston said Walker should not be confirmed.
   Walker, nominated at the urging of Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif.,
declined to return repeated telephone calls to his office and home.
   Walker's critics, however, say they see a sharp difference
between the case of Kennedy and that of Walker. They note that
Kennedy resigned from another club in 1980 after advising it of his
concern about its discriminatory policies.
   And they cite his answer before the Judiciary Committee when
asked why it took him so long to leave the Olympic Club.
   He said that over the years he had ``tried to become more
sensitive to the existence of subtle barriers to the advancement of
women and of minorities in society. And this was an issue on which
I was continuing to educate myself.''
</TEXT>
