<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-CorySpeak     05-07 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-CorySpeak,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Policy Emerges in the Philippines in Off-The-Cuff Remarks</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hours after last month's slaying of
an American colonel, President Corazon Aquino was asked her
reaction to the killing. She said U.S. security must have been
inadequate.
   A few days later, Mrs. Aquino told reporters she expected that
preliminary talks on a new treaty on U.S. military bases _ one of
the country's most divisive issues _ will begin this year.
   Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus, clearly caught by surprise at
an apparent policy reversal, issued his own statement insisting the
government still has not decided whether to allow the bases to
remain after their lease expires in 1991.
   The two statements are examples of Mrs. Aquino's tendency to
make off-the-cuff public statements, which appear overly simplistic
and display a lack of skill in communicating policy.
   ``It's amazing how President Aquino is now often caught blurting
out things that other statesmen would hesitate to say under the
same circumstances,'' said Federico Pascual, editor in chief of the
independent Philippine Daily Inquirer.
   ``We don't know if these were remarks made for calculated effect
or were lapses whose implications were not immediately clear to the
president,'' he added.
   Often, Mrs. Aquino's answers to reporters' questions on
important national issues appear aimed at dodging responsibility
and display a strangely detached view of events.
   After Communist rebels killed U.S. Army Col. James ``Nick'' Rowe
on April 21, Mrs. Aquino said American officials here had been
stepping up security but that the measures obviously were
insufficient.
   Protection of American and other foreign officials is the
responsibility of the Philippine government.
   Only later, when she visited the U.S. Embassy for a memorial
service, did she express grief at the death of an officer assigned
to assist her own armed forces.
   During a recent conversation with reporters, Mrs. Aquino was
asked to comment on reports from a left-wing West German
publication that U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt was a CIA operative.
   Instead of dismissing the claim, Mrs. Aquino suggested the State
Department should comment publicly on the charge. That appeared to
give credence to the allegation, made by former CIA operative
Philip Agee, and served to keep the charge on the front pages of
Manila newspapers for two more days.
   Eventually, Mrs. Aquino said she was satisfied with Platt's
denial of the charge.
   Mrs. Aquino's media problems are based in part on an inefficient
system of access and a haphazard formula for obtaining the
president's views and comments.
   Press Secretary Teodoro Benigno resigned last month effective
May 16, and no successor has been named. Benigno was the fourth
presidential press secretary since Mrs. Aquino took office three
years ago. His tenure was marked by frequent battles with the press
over the issue of presidential access.
   For months, reporters' access was limited largely to ``ambush''
interviews, where journalists would gather at the entrance to her
office and bark a few questions as she arrived or left.
   That was replaced by a system in which reporters would submit
daily written questions. A few hours later, reporters received
terse written replies, ostensibly from the president.
   The presidential staff has recently revived the weekly ``mini
press conference,'' in which a few Filipino reporters meet with the
president. Reporters from foreign news organizations are excluded.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Robert H. Reid has been a foreign correspondent
for The Associated Press and AP chief of bureau in Manila since
September 1986.
</TEXT>
