<FIRST>r w AM-Wright-Finances 1stAdd   05-07 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright-Finances, 1st Add,470</SECOND>
<TEXT>
   WASH: liquidation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Wright often had to borrow money to make his investments. Often,
he also relied on friends and business associates to bail him out.
His first gas well investment in 1979 with the Moncriefs is an
example.
   In 1983, both demand and prices for natural gas had declined,
and no gas was being extracted from the Moncrief well.
   By December of that year, Wright owed a bank $20,600 in
principal and interest on the loan that financed his investment in
the venture. A month later the now-deceased oilman, Monty Moncrief,
bought back Wright's interest in well for $20,000 and the speaker
used the money to pay off his loan.
   Over the 4{-year investment, Wright paid more than $30,000 in
drilling and monthly operating costs, but earned $39,353 _ $20,000
coming from the Moncrief bailout.
   Wright also had purchased from Moncrief interest in a second
east Texas well known to contain substantial quantities of natural
gas. Donald Hockaday, an independent oil and gas consultant, told
the ethics committee that deal posed no risk for Wright.
   ``I would be prone to think it was a sweetheart agreement,''
Hockaday testified. ``You know, I would love to have a chance to do
that every day.''
   Wright paid $50,000 for his interest, $35,000 of it from a bank
loan. But Hockaday calculated the value of Wright's interest at
$132,000 to $140,000, because it was clear the well would produce
gas.
   Wright held onto the well at least through late 1988, paying a
total of $56,475 in drilling and monthly operation costs and
receiving income of $74,480 from the venture, according to the
ethics committee's counsel.
   It was in 1980 that Wright and his partner, Mallick, formed
Mallightco. The company enjoyed early success through transactions
in oil stocks.
   An investment in Delhi Oil netted $83,000 in profits in five
months. Buying and selling Supron Energy Corp. stock resulted in a
$27,500 profit over 14 months, according to the ethics panel's
counsel.
   In addition, a $40,000 investment in gemstones brought in
distributions of $62,950, A profit of $41,182 was made on a Florida
real estate deal.
   But Mallightco lost money on other stock deals _ $6,314 in one
case, $1,115 in another and $700 in a third instance.
   Wright, his wife, Mallick and his wife, often had to borrow to
make Mallightco investments, sometimes borrowing from Mallightco
itself. By the end of 1981, Wright and his wife, Betty, owed their
company nearly $120,000.
   By 1984, the Wrights were no longer meeting the interest
payments on their debt owed Mallightco.
   ``The company never demanded payment from the Wrights or took
any steps to collect the debt,'' Phelan's report said.
</TEXT>
