<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     05-07 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Missiles,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Asks NATO To Play Down Missile Flap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher on Sunday said Western allies must not let a feud over
Europe's short-range nuclear missiles become the central issue of
the NATO alliance.
   Genscher also reiterated West Germany's demand that the
superpowers begin talks soon on reducing the short-range missiles.
Washington and Britain oppose the talks.
   West Germany also wants NATO to delay until 1992 a decision on
whether to modernize short-range Lance missiles based in West
Germany.
   But, in an apparent effort to tone down the dispute that has
split the alliance, he said said the disagreement should not become
a dominant issue.
   Genscher, in a speech in Stuttgart to mark the beginning of
``German-American Friendship Week,'' said: ``It would be out of all
proportion if the question of whether to decide upon a new weapons
system ... is made into the central issue of the alliance.''
   A copy of Genscher's speech was released in Bonn.
   The United States oppposes any negotiations on grounds that NATO
needs the missiles to compensate for the overwhelming superiority
of Warsaw Pact conventional forces. It also says the Lance rockets
soon will be obsolete and must be modernized to travel greater
distances.
   Most of NATO's short-range nuclear missiles are based in West
Germany. Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government is losing support in
public opinion polls and Kohl fears a decision to deploy new
missiles could cost him the next federal election in December 1990.
   Referring to a wave of reforms in the Soviet bloc, Genscher said
the Western alliance should use the ``historical opportunity'' to
forge new East-West relations.
   U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters, speaking at the same ceremony
in Stuttgart, warned NATO against ``overestimating the significance
of political changes'' in Eastern Europe.
</TEXT>
