<DOCNO> AP890507-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Election     05-07 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Election,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economic Turmoil Heralds Peronist Victory; Vote Set May 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential campaigns wind up
this week much as they began: Carlos Menem of the Peronist Party
leads in the polls and Eduardo Angeloz is plagued by his governing
party's economic failures.
   Three fringe candidates have staked out issues further to the
right and left but were expected to receive only 11 percent of the
ballots on May 14. Argentines were also to vote for one-half the
Chamber of Deputies, as well as state legislators in 16 of the 22
provinces.
   ``Angeloz could win, but his deficit is very big. If you ask me,
it isn't very likely,'' said pollster Manuel Mora y Araujo. His
survey two weeks ago gave the Radical Civic Union candidate 29
percent of the vote, with 34 percent going to Menem and 21 percent
to undecideds.
   Polls published April 30 in the capital's two largest
circulation dailies, Clarin and La Nacion, gave Menem a 10-point
edge, 36 percent to 26 percent for Angeloz. But one in four voters
was undecided.
   The main issue is the economy, which has declined for the past
four decades but plunged this year. Argentina's currency, the
austral, has been devalued by about 80 percent since February,
igniting 35 percent monthly inflation.
   Wages have not kept pace, business is in disarray, and basic
goods like medicine, milk and spare parts for industry are in short
supply or sold at several times the price of two months ago.
   Today's images of Argentina are empty shelves at pharmacies,
long lines at foreign exchange houses, a Central Bank out of paper
to print money, doctors and teachers and mail carriers on strike, a
poor housewife buying eggs and apples for her family, one at a time.
   ``I was better off five years ago than I am now,'' said Gustavo
Battiato, a 31-year-old repairman for the state telephone company.
``I voted for (President Raul) Alfonsin. I won't vote for Angeloz.''
   Angeloz, a 57-year-old provincial governor, hasn't thrown in the
towel. At rallies last week he attracted large crowds. Aides
predict 200,000 will attend his closing rally in Buenos Aires on
Tuesday.
   Angeloz's prescription for the country's economic ills is
conservative: sell inefficient state companies, balance the
national budget, encourage foreign investment, curb the power of
organized labor, increase exports, pay the foreign debt.
   Menem, a 58-year-old governor, recognizes the same problems _
triple-digit inflation, high unemployment, stagnant gross national
product, a foreign debt of $59 billion that is third highest in the
developing world _ but proposes other solutions.
   To curb the budget deficit he would raise taxes. To reduce the
burden of state companies, he would increase their efficiency
rather than sell them. To resolve the foreign debt, he would
negotiate with creditors a moratorium on payments for several years.
   The two represent different constituencies _ Angeloz, the middle
class, and Menem, organized labor, state employees and the poor.
   Apartment owners have taken their properties off the market,
fearing if elected, Menem might implement a rent freeze. Investors
have sent hundreds of millions of dollars out of the country,
fearing exchange controls under a Peronist government.
   Watching developments from the sidelines are the armed forces,
which overthrew Juan Domingo Peron in 1955, Arturo Frondizi in
1962, Arturo Illia in 1966 and Isabel Peron in 1976.
   Disgruntled officers staged three insurrections against
President Alfonsin between April 1987 and December 1988, with the
trials of officers a key grievance.
   Angeloz has tried to distance himself from an unpopular
government and capitalize on what he calls the public ``fear of
Menem.''
   At every opportunity, he brings up the street violence,
corruption and administrative incompetence of the Peronist
government headed by Isabel Peron, the general's third wife.
   Results may not be known until Aug. 10, when the Electoral
College discloses the tally of its 600 members.
   The inauguration won't be until Dec. 10, the final day of
Alfonsin's six-year term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
