<FIRST>r a AM-McChordBlacks     05-07 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McChord Blacks,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlement in Racial Bias Suit at McChord AFB</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has tentatively approved a
settlement of a decade-old class-action racial discrimination
lawsuit filed by black civilian employees of McChord Air Force Base.
   U.S. District Court Judge Robert Bryan said Friday that he found
the settlement fair and reasonable, but the agreement won't be
final before mid-August.
   About 125 current and former black employees who were denied
promotions they sought or who were discouraged from applying are
eligible to receive a total of $415,000 in back wages the
government agreed to pay under the agreement. The suit included
about 300 current and former black employees.
   Williams said payments should range between about $500 and
$15,000.
   The settlement is designed to correct what black employees said
was a system that fostered discrimination in promotions at the
base. The federal government did not admit wrongdoing in the
agreement.
   ``I'm very confident that the people in the civilian personnel
office will make a legitimate effort to ensure that what occurred
in the past does not occur in the future,'' said Sidney A.
Williams, who has worked at McChord for 33 years and filed the
original claim in 1979.
   ``If nobody ever complains, nothing ever changes,'' Williams
said.
   The preliminary settlement provides for the promotions of 12
blacks to currently vacant supervisory positions or higher-paying
positions that eventually could lead to supervisory posts.
   The promoted blacks also would participate in future promotion
decisions at McChord.
   Raphael Gomez, attorney for the Air Force, said he wouldn't
comment on the settlement.
   The federal government fought the case for more than 10 years,
the first four in a fruitless effort to prevent the suit from being
certified as a class action.
</TEXT>
