<FIRST>r a AM-People     05-07 1083</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,1128</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Racing high-powered cars at perilous
speeds is a form of relaxation for Paul Newman, according to the
track owner who has been watching the actor unwind from his present
movie chores.
   Newman is in town to film ``Blaze,'' the story of former Gov.
Earl K. Long's controversial 1950s relationship with New Orleans
stripper Blaze Starr.
   About 2,000 people crowded Baton Rouge Raceway here Friday night
to see Newman, who came from the movie set still costumed in a
black tuxedo and red socks.
   Newman was scheduled to present awards to race winners, but
showed up before the featured races were run. So he made a brief
speech, exhorting the crowd to ``raise hell,'' and left.
   Track owner Donald Watson said he had opened up his track for
Newman three times last week so the actor, who's also a leading
race driver, could ``wind down'' by racing on its dirt track.
   ``He enjoys racing. It's a way for him to wind down. Racing
totally takes your mind off other things,'' said Watson.
   ``It's not a hobby. Paul takes it seriously,'' Watson said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Giants linebacker Lawrence Taylor is one of
five investors who bought a $1.1 million 50-unit apartment building
here.
   Taylor, an All-Pro linebacker who lives in Upper Saddle River,
will be key owner of the building, his lawyer, James R. Acheson,
said Saturday.
   Pamela Goldstein, spokeswoman for Newark Mayor Sharpe James,
confirmed Saturday that Taylor had closed on some property. Ms.
Goldstein said she was told the building would be ``affordable
housing.''
   Although Taylor has never lived in Newark, he wants to bring
better housing to the state's largest city, Acheson said.
   He said the mayor ``invited (Taylor) down to visit the mayor's
office and the two of them got along very well. Sharpe James wants
people to invest in Newark ... and Lawrence Taylor took him up on
it.''
   ``We felt this is a good example for other people who have made
it big in sports ... and other professional people,'' Ms. Goldstein
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDEPENDENCE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clara Hale, an 84-year-old New York
City woman who nurtures children born to drug addicts and AIDS
patients, was awarded the 16th annual Truman Award for Public
Service.
   ``Doing this is what makes me happy,'' she said. ``God put us
here with brains to think and do, and we're here to help one
another. When you do that, you radiate.
   ``I feel really good. I'm working for that day when God calls me
home and says, `Well done.'''
   Independence Mayor Barbara Potts presented the award on the
steps of the Truman Library in Independence Saturday. She noted
that Mrs. Hale ``did not wait for a government program'' to give
babies a second chance through nurturing and love.
   Lorraine E. Hale, Mrs. Hale's daughter and executive director of
the Hale House in New York City, summed up her mother's philosophy:
``These children are all born good. They're born honest. And they
need a lot of love.''
   Mrs. Hale said she teaches all of her little ones to say two
things: ``please'' and ``thank you.''
   And she told the crowd, ``Please invite me again and thank you
so much.'' Hale House was born in 1969 when Mrs. Hale discovered a
child in the arms of an addict on a New York street corner. Since
then, she and her daughter have helped raise more than 600 infants
in the non-profit residential program, operating in a Harlem
brownstone.
   Mrs. Hale's efforts became widely known after then-President
Reagan singled her out for praise as an example of voluntarism.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The high school math teacher whose career
was chronicled in the movie ``Stand and Deliver'' told graduating
University of South Carolina students to remain committed to
education and set high goals.
   ``I believe in what I'm doing and I believe in education _ it is
the ticket to success,'' Jaime Escalante told undergraduates at the
ceremony Saturday.
   But Escalante, 58, warned that the country's educational system
is not keeping pace with other countries'.
   ``Our system of education needs a new schematic. We have to
rebuild,'' he said. ``We're falling behind because we are not
teaching responsibility. We must become a nation of people who
think for a living.''
   Escalante received an honorary doctor of science degree from the
university. His efforts to teach high-level mathematics to
inner-city Los Angeles youths inspired the movie, in which he was
portrayed by ``Miami Vice'' star Edward James Olmos.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Reagan will be among the
celebrities scheduled to appear July 21 during opening ceremonies
of U.S. Olympic Festival.
   The festival, conducted during non-Olympic years, will take
place in several Oklahoma communities from July 21-30.
   ``I am honored to be a part of the opening of this event which
is so important to the development of America's athletes,'' Reagan
said in a statement released Saturday by the committee. ``The U.S.
Olympic Festival has become a vital component in the preparation of
the young people who represent our future in Olympic competition.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hunger activist Bob Geldof, after blasting the
media for getting in the way of world understanding, urged the
creation of a global broadcast university.
   ``It is essential that people be given access to information on
matters that influence them,'' Geldof told a gathering Saturday of
international contributors to the ``CNN World Report,'' a
production of Cable News Network.
   Geldof, an Irish rock musician and composer, organized the Live
Aid benefit concert that raised $72 million for African famine
victims in 1985. That concert sparked similar efforts, including
one announced Friday by Turner Broadcasting System and Jesse
Jackson to aid victims of the Dec. 7 earthquake in Armenia.
   Geldof said Jackson has asked for his help in that eight-hour
concert, scheduled for Aug. 12.
   Calling television ``a hindrance to understanding'' and ``the
single worst anti-democratic force in the world today,'' Geldof
told the broadcasters the mass media concentrates on images, quick
interviews and controversy at the expense of improving
understanding.
   ``Controversy is not necessarily information,'' he said.
``Giving facts is not enough.''
   He called on broadcasters to communicate directly to the people
in rural areas of the Third World. Geldof suggested distributing
solar-powered radios to people in areas lacking electricity so they
could tune in to the global university, which should offer
``recognized degrees.''
</TEXT>
