<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-89 1439EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NewCoke Bjt   05-07 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Coke, Bjt,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>4 Years Later, New Coke Still Hasn't Caught On With Consumers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Coke is 4 years old and an also-ran in the
cola wars, but Coca-Cola Co. says there's plenty of fizz left in
the beverage that helped revolutionize the marketing of soft drinks.
   Coca-Cola was the world's most popular soft drink and more. The
brand had become a symbol of the pervasive influence of American
power and culture around the globe.
   So it was no small decision when the company decided to
reformulate the cola it had sold for 99 years. And it triggered no
small reaction. The consumer backlash to the new drink was so
strong that the company quickly brought back the original formula
under the name Coca-Cola Classic.
   Four years later, what goes by the label of Coke is virtually
ignored by consumers while Classic Coke reigns No. 1. But company
officials say they have no plans to drop the new formula, and
industry analysts say they're right.
   ``It's regarded as the absolute biggest marketing travesty ever
hoisted on the American public. With God's help, everyone will have
similar mistakes,'' said Jesse Meyers, who publishes Beverage
Digest in Greenwich, Conn.
   ``The announcement of new Coke gave new birth to all Coca-Cola
products and the entire soft drink industry,'' he said.
   The introduction of the new Coke heated up the ``cola wars,''
and saw companies step up their efforts to introduce new variations
of their name-brand products to gain a greater share of the $45
billion soft-drink market. Now there is not only Coke and Classic
Coke, but diet Coke, caffeine-free Coke and even regular and diet
Cherry Coke.
   Arch-rival Pepsico may regard the new Coke as a ``pretty nominal
player,'' but it believes a company's full product line is more
important than any single drink, said spokesman Todd MacKenzie.
   ``The parts make up the whole,'' MacKenzie said.
   Indeed, Coca-Cola emphasizes that its entire line of soft drinks
is strong and claims to hold a dominant 33.7 percent share of the
retail market.
   The brand name with the new formula that for years was the
best-seller had dropped to 10th place at the end of 1988, tied with
RC Cola and caffeine-free Diet Pepsi. The new Coke had a mere 1.4
percent of the market, down from 1.6 percent in 1987, according to
Beverage Digest.
   By contrast, Classic Coke _ the old Coke with the new name _
held the No. 1 position with 20.1 percent of the market. Pepsi Cola
was No. 2 with 18.7 percent.
   Even with its slim market share, the new Coke makes money and
generates $675 million a year in revenue, said Randy Donaldson, a
spokesman at the company's Atlanta headquarters.
   ``If Coca-Cola had any other name on it, it would be perceived
as a huge success,'' Donaldson said. ``Because the can has
`Coca-Cola' on it, the expectations were huge.''
   Emanuel Goldman, a soft drink industry analyst with Paine Webber
Inc. in San Francisco, said the new Coke still sold 4 billion cans
last year, which makes it unlikely the company would drop it.
   ``There are people still drinking it,'' he said. ``If they take
it away, they may go somewhere else.''
   Donaldson said taste tests continue to show consumers like new
Coke better than Pepsi.
   Improving the taste was behind the decision to alter the
formula, the company said when it announced the change in April
1985.
   The new Coke hit the stores on May 8 of that year, the 99th
anniversary of the date the first Coca-Cola was sold. But
notwithstanding test results, the backlash was swift and harsh from
consumers who resented the removal of a drink they had enjoyed for
generations.
   Two months later, Coca-Cola apologized to the public and brought
back the old formula as Classic Coke.
   ``There's no question it didn't work out as planned,'' Donaldson
said.
   Still, the bungling hasn't tarnished the vaunted brand name,
Meyers asserts.
   ``In the public's mind, what they call Coke is what the company
is Atlanta calls Coca-Cola Classic,'' he said.
</TEXT>
