<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-89 1523EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-07 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Having breakfast with the ``god of
thunder'' may not be everyone's cup of tea, but it's just what John
Fitzpatrick wanted.
   ``God of thunder'' in this case is a hairy,
not-quite-2-month-old gorilla at the San Francisco Zoo, where it's
the first baby gorilla born in 14 years.
   Fitzpatrick won the zoo's name-that-gorilla contest with his
suggestion that the cuddly little fellow should be named Shango,
which means ``god of thunder'' among the Yoruba-speaking people of
Nigeria. His idea beat more than 100 other entries.
   Senior primate keeper Carol Martinez said last week that the
name Shango was chosen because a troop of gorillas was recently
discovered in Nigeria, where the name originates.
   She said gorillas were thought to be extinct there ``and this
discovery is a hopeful sign for the survival of the lowland
gorilla.''
   As his prize for naming Shango, Fitzpatrick will breakfast soon
with the little one, mama Bawang and daddy Mkubwa. He'll get to eat
at a table set up in a part of the gorilla building not open to the
public that gives a great view of the primates, the zoo said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GREENEVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The doghouse or the henhouse? Foghorn
is a bit confused about home.
   The rooster has turned up his beak at the hens on Polly
Johnson's farm to share a large, turned-over barrel with a
friendly, female mutt named Muffin.
   ``What we have here is a pretty unnatural situation,'' Mrs.
Johnson said.
   Foghorn is a silky rooster rather than one of the more popular
varieties of farm roosters, such as Rhode Island Red, she said. His
feathers are unique _ ``more like hair,'' she said. ``Maybe that's
why he thinks he belongs in the doghouse instead of the henhouse.''
   Muffin, a medium-sized dog with German shepherd features,
doesn't seem to mind the company. The two are pals and sleep
together in the barrel turned on its side that serves as Muffin's
home.
   Mrs. Johnson tried to confine the rooster with the hens after
she was given Foghorn this spring, but he wouldn't have anything to
do with his own kind and soon sought out the dog.
   ``He doesn't seem to care a thing about the hens,'' Mrs. Johnson
said.
   Muffin recently got away from her feathered companion long
enough to mate with her own species. She's the mother of a new
litter.
   ``When it comes to dogs, people will believe about anything, but
they won't believe ... Muffin and Foghorn until they see it,'' Mrs.
Johnson said. ``After they see it, they get a funny look on their
face.''
</TEXT>
