<FIRST>r a AM-MoodyBeach     05-07 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Moody Beach,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beach Owners Reject Opening of Land They Fought to Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WELLS, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moody Beach property owners, who won a court
battle over control of access to the mile-long stretch of sandy
shore, reacted angrily Sunday as town officials proposed that the
beach be reopened to the public anyway.
   ``I object to allowing hordes of people to come onto my
property,'' landowner Andy Galt said at a special meeting called by
Town Manager Jonathan Carter. ``This is private land. Every one of
us knows that.''
   Even though the town of Wells and the state attorney general's
office were the losers in late March when the Maine Supreme Court
ruled that the property owners can bar the public from the beach,
Carter told landowners Sunday that the town would agree to maintain
the beach if it could be opened to the public.
   ``The town will comply with the court decision,'' Carter said.
``In the short term, we want to see ... if the property owners
would consider opening it up for the summer, the summer of 1989.''
   The town is seeking an appraisal of the beach to consider taking
it through eminent domain, and Carter found no enthusiasm for his
proposal to keep the beach public in the meantime.
   ``I don't feel that you people considered that these are
individual pieces of land,'' property owner Dorothy Jones said.
``We are not operating as a country club group or a condominium
group. I may decide on Tuesday I'll let everybody there. On
Wednesday, I may get up grumpy and say, `Nobody.' I intend to keep
that right.''
   Sandy shore is rare in Maine, making up just 35 miles of the
3,500-mile meandering coastline, which is mostly rocky.
   The divided supreme court ruled in March that the only public
access right to the beach was granted in a 17th century colonial
ordinance that permits access for fishing, bird hunting and boating.
   Mrs. Jones and other Moody Beach owners complained that for
years, thousands of tourists have come to the beach without
respecting their property.
   The landowners asked town selectmen Sunday whether it would be
possible to stop local motels and campgrounds from bringing in
tourists on buses, but Town Attorney Gordon Ayer said there would
be constitutional problems with such a ban.
   After the landowners made it clear they would not consider
opening the beach to the public, Carter said that the town will
abide by the court ruling. But he has said it will be difficult to
keep tourists away.
</TEXT>
