<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--AppleContest     05-07 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Apple Contest,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apple Computer Rescinds Boys-Only Rule In Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boys-only contest sponsored by Apple
Computer, which offered a week at a basketball camp run by Los
Angeles Laker Magic Johnson, was opened to girls when officials
called it discriminatory.
   Apple announced late last week that girls could join the ``Magic
of Apple'' contest and attend the camp if they win. Drawings were
being held in computer stores in several Southern California
counties to determine the winners.
   Feminist attorney Gloria Allred called the boys-only contest
unlawful, and Marian Johnston, civil rights supervisor at the state
Justice Department, also said the contest was discriminatory.
   ``I'm glad someone brought it up to them,'' said Lon Rosen,
co-owner of the Magic Johnson camp. ``If girls want to get into the
Magic Johnson camp, we obviously will allow them.''
   Girls have attended the camp in the past, he said. Sharon
Stevenson, an Apple staff member who coordinated advertising for
the contest, said she had not known that the basketball camp
admitted girls.
