<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan-Relief 1stLd-Writethru a0658 05-07 0876</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Relief, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Food Stockpiles Grow in Rebel-Held Sudanese Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 5th pvs, `Operation Lifeline-Sudan...,'
to UPDATE with official's comments on progress of operation. Pick up 6th
pvs, `Deliveries could...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORIT, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The relief plane executed a corkscrew dive
in case of missile attack, leveled off and landed in Torit, a
once-bustling southern town transformed by civil war and fa mine
into a dusty rebel outpost.
   Shoeless young men, wearing only tattered shorts and glistening
with sweat, unloaded the 14 tons of maize. It was the plane's
second delivery of the day.
   Under the shade of a mango tree beyond a ridge of earthen
fortifications, rebels in army fatigues and civilians in ragged
clothing relaxed and watched what has become a regular exercise.
   The airlift is part of a program coordinated by the United
Nations to save 100,000 southern Sudanese from starvation by
stocking food throughout the region before the annual rains, which
begin this month and will make roads and airstrips unusable.
   Operation Lifeline-Sudan, begun April 1 and expected to cost
$132 million, is intended to prevent a repeat of last year's
disaster.
   The director of the operation said Sunday that it was well
behind schedule but ``virtually certain'' to stave off massive
starvation.
   ``The back of the disaster has been broken,'' the director,
James P. Grant, told a Nairobi news conference.
   He said about 45,000 tons of food and supplies has been moved
into southern Sudan and another 50,000 tons is expected to be moved
into the region by the end of June.
   The operation's deadline was pushed back a month due to the
delays and will continue to deliver food into southern Sudan
through the rainy season, said Grant.
   Deliveries could not begin until the government and rebels
agreed to suspend fighting along specified ``corridors of
tranquility'' along which the food and other supplies could move.
Aid is being sent to both rebel-held areas and those controlled by
the army.
   A monthlong truce followed the initial agreement, but the
original goal of stockpiling 170,000 tons of supplies in the south
still is unlikely to be achieved.
   Relief officials say as many as 500,000 people died of drought,
flood and famine exacerbated by the 6-year-old war between the army
and the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army led by former Col.
John Garang.
   Most southern Sudanese are black, predominantly Christian or
animist. Garang and his rebel army are fighting for autonomy and a
better economic deal from the government in the Arab, Moslem north.
   No one knows for sure how many of Torit's 30,000 people perished
before rebel fighters drove out the last soldiers in February,
ending a yearlong siege of this river town ringed by the jagged
Imatong Mountains. U.N. officials estimate up to 1,000 died each
month.
   Rebels found fewer than 1,000 civilians remaining in the town's
huts of mud and thatch, relief officials said. The rest had died or
fled into the bush to escape the war and to forage for food.
   Residents who stayed or have returned since February say they
were denied any of the supplies government soldiers received
through army airdrops and survived on mangoes and a clover-like
weed the local Latuga tribe calls ogasik.
   Laudina Legga, 28, said 15 members of her family starved to
death before she, her mother and her two children fled to the bush
early this year.
   ``We ate only ogasik for nine months,'' she said in a
conversation on a dirt road. Ms. Legga was returning home from the
relief plane with a basket of maize balanced on her head.
   She and the others returned to Torit at the end of April, lured
by the new security and growing stocks of food. The United Nations
says about 20,000 people have come back to the town and surrounding
area since the rebels took control.
   Many huts still appeared empty during a tour of the town. People
interviewed seemed in good health and relatively well-fed.
   Olaug Husby, one of three Norwegian Church Aid health workers
based in Torit, said the apparent lack of hunger was partly due to
resumed harvesting of food from the countryside. Other relief
officials said the people may not have been as desperate this year
as had been thought.
   Whatever the explanation, ``they are not starving now,'' said
Ben Martinson, a U.N. representative coordinating storage in Torit.
   He said some of the relief food had been distributed but most
would be stockpiled for the rainy season, when floods normally
isolate Torit until November.
   U.N. officials expect the town's population to reach 50,000,
with the influx of refugees, and plan to stock 8,000 tons of food.
Martinson said about a quarter of that had been delivered by May 1,
two weeks after airlifts and road convoys started moving from
Uganda and Kenya.
   Convoys from Kenya were suspended May 1, three days after the
second attack along the road. Eight rebel escorts were killed April
18, when a missile destroyed the lead vehicle in the first attack
on a relief convoy.
   Martinson said he suspected the raids were carried out by
tribesmen in the area or by Ugandan insurgents who had filtered
into southern Sudan.
</TEXT>
