<FIRST>r i AM-Panama-Scene     05-07 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Scene,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Determined Voters Ignore Hot Sun, Dust</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in lines that snaked across an
empty lot Sunday were not discouraged by a hot tropical sun as they
waited patiently to cast their ballots in Panama's second
presidential election in 21 years.
   Some brought parasols or even chairs for the wait. Others turned
out before dawn, two hours before polls opened at 7 a.m., while
still others just sweated in the sun.
   ``Everybody votes in the morning, then goes home to wait,'' said
Nellida Galvez, an opposition party pollwatcher.
   Voting was slowed by late-opening polls, careful checks of
booths by pollwatchers and the somewhat cumbersome process of
casting ballots. But voters remained in the long lines.
   Election officials sat at a rough wooden table with party
pollwatchers arrayed behind them at ballot box 2742, inside one of
seven sheds placed on a dusty lot in downtown Panama City.
   Voters stepped up to the bench and proferred their identity
cards, which were checked and punched. A man whose ID card did not
quite match the registration list was allowed to cast his ballot
after a quick discussion among poll officials and pollwatchers.
   ``We all know each other here,'' said one official. ``The
instructions say to assume minor problems are just mistakes or
typos.''
   The turnout at 2742, as at others throughout the nation, was
extremely heavy. By 8 a.m. more than 100 of the 348 people assigned
to the station were in line, but only 20 people had voted.
   ``I've been on line an hour and it looks like I have another
hour to wait,'' said Felipe Reynaud, his skin shiny with sweat.
``But I'm going to vote.''
   At one voting station, acting president Manuel Solis Palma was
greeted with a mixture of boos and cheers.
   Opposition presidential candidate Guillermo Endara appeared at
another polling booth and was greeted by a joyous, chanting crowd.
   It was a calm Sunday, and Panama City's streets were almost
entirely empty. No liquor sales were permitted between noon
Saturday and midnight Sunday.
   U.S.-style ballots are not used in the voting process in Panama.
Voters are given an empty envelope when they enter a booth. Inside
are stacks of colored cards for each candidate. A voter puts the
cards of the candidates he supports into the envelope, then
deposits the envelope into a cardboard urn.
   Loud cheers broke out when a woman who had taken fully five
minutes to complete the process finally emerged. Poll officials
brought forward the elderly and the handicapped, saying they did
not have to wait in line.
   Complaints were minor. Voters at one booth said they tried to
disguise their motions as they selected their cards because the
curtain was too short and allowed officials to see inside.
   Pollwatchers at box 2742 complained that the booth's light bulb
had been stolen, which would complicate the initial count after
polls close at 5 p.m.
   ``I'll get a flashlight,'' said Ricardo Duran, another
opposition pollwatcher.
   ``No, I'll have my father bring a light bulb from home,'' said
Galvez.
</TEXT>
