<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-89 1705EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0675 05-07 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outgoing President Endorses Rafsanjani as Successor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS four grafs with Khamenei criticizing West for support of
Rushdie.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian President Ali Khamenei on Sunday
indirectly endorsed as his successor Parliament speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani, who has urged a terror campaign against Westerners to
avenge the deaths of Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied lands.
   Khamenei also backed constitutional reforms that are expected to
give the president more executive power, said Iran's official
Islamic Republic News Agency.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Khamenei as telling
worshipers in Tehran, ``Fortunately, the people's attention has
naturally been drawn to one of the most prominent faces of the
Islamic Republic.''
   Khamenei did not mention Rafsanjani by name but made an obvious
reference to him, saying: ``The candidate that some groups have
identified for the presidency revives this hope in us that, God
willing, our nation will have a much brighter future.''
   Rafsanjani, 54, one of Iran's most prominent political
personalities, is the only declared candidate so far in
presidential elections scheduled for late summer. Two influential
clerical groups, one composed of hardliners and the other of
liberal theologians, have said they will back the parliament
speaker.
   Khamenei, a longtime political ally of Rafsanjani, made the
endorsement during a sermon to mark the Eid al-Fitr feast that ends
the Moslem holy month of Ramadan.
   ``God willing, this year the matter of the presidency will be
good news for our people,'' he said.
   Under the 1980 constitution, the 50-year-old president cannot
run for a third four-year term.
   Rafsanjani, who also serves as acting commander of the armed
forces, earned a reputation as a moderate through his support for
rebuilding ties with Western nations. He hoped to speed
reconstruction of the country after the eight-year-long Persian
Gulf war, halted by a U.N.-mediated cease-fire on Aug. 20.
   But he recently changed tack, supporting Iranian leader
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomenei's Feb. 14 call for the death of British
author Salman Rushdie.
   And in an inflammatory speech broadcast Friday, Rafsanjani said
five American, French or British citizens should be killed in
retaliation for each Arab slain in the uprising in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. He urged Palestinians to
hijack planes or blow up factories in Western countries in order to
pressure Israel to release prisoners.
   Last month, Rafsanjani backed a decision by Khomeini to amend
the constitution and said he hoped the reforms would give the next
president more power.
   Executive power is divided between Khamenei and Prime Minister
Hussein Musavi. Khomeini has the last word in decision-making as
the country's spiritual leader.
   But the prime minister holds more authority than the president,
and Khamenei has said that must be rectified if Iran is to have a
strong government.
   Khomeini appointed a 20-man committee to revise the
constitution, which must then be approved by the people in a
referendum.
   Both Rafsanjani and Khamenei are committee members. Analysts
have speculated the committee may suggest the prime minister's job
be abolished altogether.
   In his sermon, Khamenei was quoted as saying a stronger
presidency and constitutional reforms would allow ``greater room
for realizing the nation's potential.''
   Also Sunday, the president opened the Tehran International Book
Fair with an attack on the West for supporting Rushdie's book ``The
Satanic Verses,'' the official news agency reported.
   ``We can see how colonialist hands are supporting a writer and
publishers who have insulted the sanctities of 1 billion Moslems,''
the agency quoted Khamenei as saying.
   The book prompted worldwide protests by Moslems, who view it as
blasphemous. Rushdie has been in hiding since Khomeini called for
his death.
   The news agency said despite a boycott by some Western
publishers, 237 foreign publishers and 270 local companies are
participating in the 12-day fair.
