<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   05-07 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0684,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Body Of Missing Israeli Soldier Found, 15 Arabs Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with details, five more reported wounded,
moves up material on soldier's body found. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of an Israeli paratrooper sergeant who
was missing since Feb. 16 was found Sunday buried near the occupied
Gaza Strip, and Israeli officials accused Palestinian guerrillas of
killing him.
   Hundreds of angry Israelis gathered outside the victim's home in
the port city of Ashdod, shouting ``Death to the Arabs!''
   Israel radio said some Israelis attacked an Arab laborer at a
nearby grocery store. It said police rescued the Arab and sealed
off the area.
   Also Sunday, Arab hospital officials said 15 Palestinians were
shot and wounded in clashes with soldiers, despite widespread
curfews ordering 450,000 Palestinians to stay in their homes.
   Twelve of the wounded were shot in clashes in Rafah, Gaza City
and three refugee camps, the hospital officials said. They said at
least three were shot in the occupied West Bank. The army said it
had no reports of woundings.
   The slain soldier, Avi Sassportaz, 21, disappeared after leaving
his southern base for his home. He was last seen hitchhiking at a
junction about 10 miles from the Gaza Strip.
   ``There is no doubt it's homicide. Preliminary findings show he
was shot,'' an army spokesman said. Israel radio, however, said a
knife was found near the body.
   The radio said Sassportaz was found when private investigators
who were searching for stolen cars in a helicopter landed and
spotted a hand sticking out of the ground.
   The army, backed by police and volunteers, had searched
extensively for Sassportaz since his disappearance. At one point,
the search covered 200 square miles and involved 22,500 people.
   Late in February, a caller claiming to represent the Palestinian
Arab Army, a previously unknown group, told the Agence France
Presse news agency and Israel radio the group was holding
Sassportaz. It demanded the release of 1,500 Palestinians.
   Meanwhile, some 1,300 soldiers carried out a massive search in
the area north of Gaza for another Israeli soldier believed
kidnapped.
   The soldier, Ilan Saadon, 18, was last seen Wednesday getting
into a white car driven by men wearing skullcaps of observant Jews.
   ``We don't know if there is a link, whether this (was done by)
the same guerrilla group,'' Police Minister Chaim Bar-Lev told
Israel radio. ``So far, he is missing.''
   ``This disguise, passing off as religious people, we are
familiar with this technique,'' he added.
   Saadon's tearful mother said on Israel Television that ``This
boy is my soul...I'm only asking God to let him come back in
peace.''
   Sassportaz's death raised to 21 the number of Israelis killed in
the 17-month Arab uprising, along with 465 Palestinians.
   The army said Sunday its investigation of Saturday's clashes in
the Gaza Strip showed two Palestinians were killed and 77 wounded
as soldiers opened fire to quell protests on Eid Al-Fitr, a major
Moslem holiday.
   Arab hospital officials reported three killed and 135 injured in
the Saturday violence. The toll of wounded was the highest in a
single day in Gaza since the start of the uprising.
   In Tel Aviv, Chief Military Spokesman Brig. Gen. Ephraim Lapid
defended the army against Palestinians' charges that the presence
of soldiers outside a mosque in the Nusseirat refugee camp provoked
the clashes Saturday.
   ``The local people in Gaza ... searched for confrontation with
Israeli soldiers.''
   According to Arab reports, the trouble Saturday began as Moslems
leaving morning prayers found about 100 soldiers waiting outside
the mosque. Stone-throwing started and the troops opened fire.
   Also in the West Bank, Jewish settlers announced they founded a
new settlement near Nahalin, the Arab village where five
Palestinians were killed last month in one of the worst
confrontations with Israeli forces in the uprising.
   More than 70,000 Israelis already live in about 130 settlements
among the 1.7 million Palestinians in the occupied lands. The U.S.
government has called the settlements an obstacle to peace.
</TEXT>
