<FIRST>r a AM-People-HankWilliams     05-07 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Hank Williams,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Country Music Star's Jet Seized After Brief, Profanity-Filled Appearance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note 2nd graf. Roxson cq in 12th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at a concert arena got an
order seizing Hank Williams Jr.'s private jet Sunday to cover
expenses of a brief, profanity-filled appearance in which the
country music star failed to finish a single song.
   But a spokesman for the singer said Williams, 39, was sorry
about Saturday night's concert at the Baton Rouge Centroplex and
would put everything right.
   After the concert ended, a few among the 7,000 concert-goers
threw bottles and tried to burn souvenir T-shirts, said police, but
there were no injuries or arrests reported. Damage to the building
was described as minor.
   Michael M. Pierce, director of the 11,000-seat arena, said the
singer ``would do three or four bars ... and then use some
profanity and say `We don't need this song,' and then immediately
sing something else.''
   After about 20 minutes during which he talked incoherently and
attempted several songs, Williams threw his fiddle into the air and
stumbled offstage, helped by members of his entourage, witnesses
said.
   Fans had been told by a member of Williams entourage that they
could get their money back at the box office, but the box office
didn't have that kind of cash on hand, Pierce said.
   ``The folks were aggravated,'' said Police Chief Wayne Rogillio.
``We understood it. All we tried to do was try contain them from
damaging anybody or anything. I think we were successful to some
extent.''
   Williams, who was voted Academy of Country Music entertainer of
the year three times, was apologetic and promised to pay for ticket
refunds, other expenses and any profit the arena would have made,
spokesman Kent Arwood said Sunday.
   Arwood, interviewed by telephone from his home in Nashville,
said the incident was caused by a personal problem he would not
disclose, and bore no relationship to the incident last month in
which Williams stormed offstage 40 minutes into a concert in
Bristol, Tenn.
   Arwood said several times that Williams is not an alcoholic and
that a problem he had acknowledge having with pills is a thing of
the past. His father, the famous country singer-songwriter Hank
Williams Sr., died in 1953 at age 29 of the effects of alcohol
abuse.
</TEXT>
