<FIRST>r p AM-TexasMayoralRdp     05-07 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Mayoral Rdp,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayors Chosen in San Antonio, Dallas, Fort Worth; El Paso Race In
Runoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former San Antonio mayor has her old job
back and the mayors in Fort Worth and Dallas have been returned to
office by wide margins.
   In El Paso, two council members will face each other in a May 27
runoff to determine who will lead that struggling border city.
   While former San Antonio Mayor Lila Cockrell, Fort Worth Mayor
Bob Bolen and Dallas Mayor Annette Strauss coasted to easy
victories Saturday, the two El Paso candidates squeaked past four
others to set up the runoff.
   Council members Suzy Azar and Mayor Pro-Tem Ed Elsey will face
each other to determine who will succeed Jonathan Rogers, who by
law could not run for a fifth, two-year term.
   Ms. Azar had 16,220 votes, or 31 percent, compared with 11,930
votes or 23 percent for Elsey. Close beind Elsey was state Rep.
Paul Moreno, with 10,452 or 20 percent. Three other candidates had
a combined 27 percent of the vote.
   In San Antonio, Ms. Cockrell, who was mayor between 1975 and
1981, received 45,300 votes, or 59 percent, from a seven-candidate
field and on June 1 will replace Mayor Henry Cisneros, who chose
not to seek a fifth two-year term.
   Ms. Cockrell's closest challenger, insurance executive Carl S.
Mauthe, received about 31 percent of the vote.
   ``I'm just very, very grateful to the citizens for giving me
this opportunity again and I think it's a matter of my having gone
back to the voters and gotten reacquainted and worked very hard and
offered my services if the voters wished to have me return,'' Ms.
Cockrell said.
   In Dallas, Mrs. Strauss, backed by a huge campaign fund and the
business community, pulled 73 percent of the vote in a race with
three opponents.
   She had garnered 60,895 votes, compared with 17,002 or 20
percent for leading challenger Peter Lesser. The two other
candidates managed no more than 4 percent of the vote each.
   ``The stage is now set for building opportunities, growth and
prosperity and we will all share in the good years that are
ahead,'' Ms. Strauss said.
   In Fort Worth, Bolen was re-elected to his fourth two-year term,
receiving 89 percent of the vote, compared with 7 percent for his
nearest challenger, Evelyn Williams.
   The San Antonio ballot was the first one in 14 years that didn't
include Cisneros, who was a city councilman for six years before
becoming mayor in 1981.
   The popular 41-year-old mayor, beset by a troubled marriage and
his son's ill health, said last fall that he wouldn't run again and
would accept a job in the private sector.
</TEXT>
