<FIRST>r a AM-Coma-Birth 1stLd-Writethru a0656 05-07 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coma-Birth, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0656,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Wrote Poem Five Months After Giving Birth in a Coma</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to restore first reference to other driver, Byron
Stackhouse.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than five months after she gave birth
while in a coma, Barbara Blodgett has composed a poem and is
learning to eat, dress and groom herself.
   In a meeting with reporters Saturday outside the family's rented
home, the 24-year-old woman said little more than ``hi,'' sitting
in a wheelchair with her eyes fixed on her husband, David.
   He said she composed the following poem to him on a computer
keyboard:
   ``I know in my heart what is wrong, what is right
   ``I know in my heart our love is worth the fight
   ``So hold on to me, babe, hold me tight, hold me fast,
   ``I know in my heart our love is going to last.''
   As he sat beside his wife, Blodgett gave a bottle to their son,
Simon, who was born in Seattle by Caesarean section Dec. 9, five
months after Mrs. Blodgett was injured in an automobile accident.
   She was the fourth woman in recorded medical history to carry a
healthy fetus to term while in a coma.
   Mrs. Blodgett was three months pregnant when the vehicle in
which she was riding collided with another vehicle June 30,
injuring nerves between her brain and the spinal cord. Her cousin,
Nicole Valenzuela, was killed.
   Blodgett, who was wearing a seat belt, and David Blodgett III,
then 13 months and strapped into a car seat, escaped injury.
   Doctors had held out little hope that Mrs. Blodgett would
recover, but she began to regain consciousness after her son was
born.
   Since Feb. 14 she has spent most of her time in rehabilitation
therapy at St. Elizabeth Medical Center, visiting her family at
home on weekends.
   A statement issued by hospital officials said she had learned to
eat, was learning to drink liquids and was trying to become mobile
enough to get into and out of bed, dress and groom herself and
perform other functions. She is able to stand only with assistance.
   Now that she has mastered the use of a keyboard, the next step
is learning to use a device that translates typed messages into
human speech.
   Blodgett said he returned to work a month ago after using up
sick leave and vacation time donated by co-workers at the U.S.
Forest Service, where he and his wife worked before the accident.
   ``I've learned a lot more about responsibility,'' he said.
   The other driver, Byron Stackhouse, who was slightly injured,
was convicted of vehicular assault and sentenced to three years in
prison. Testimony indicated his blood alcohol content after the
accident was more than twice the legal threshhold for driving while
intoxicated.
</TEXT>
