<FIRST>r i AM-Armenia     05-07 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Armenia,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Try Carrot to Quell Armenian Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities who fear more ethnic strife took a
conciliatory tone with Armenian protesters Sunday, dispersing
several thousand of them with a pledge to allow a rally later this
week, a local journalist said.
   Gen. Maj. Mikhail Surkhov of the local military district
confronted the protesters in Yerevan, the capital of Armenia,
according to an editor with Armenpress, the republic's official
news agency. He persuaded the crowd to break up by assuring them a
legal demonstration could be held on Thursday, the journalist said.
   The editor, who spoke in a telephone interview on condition of
anonymity, said the protesters were demanding freedom for members
of the Karabakh Committee who have been jailed since December. The
group led calls last year for the annexation of Nagorno-Karabakh,
an Armenian-dominated region of neighboring Azerbaijan.
   The dispute between the two southwestern republics led to the
deaths of more than 90 people in ethnic violence last year. The
Kremlin placed the disputed region under its own control.
   A new round of ethnic protests broke out last week.
   Local activist Rafael Popoyan, also speaking by telephone,
reported strikes by students outside the university and other
schools in Yerevan.
   He said Yerevan authorities arrested Movzes Gogkesian, editor of
the magazine Motherland, for an unknown reason.
   Popoyan also said a general strike was continuing in
Nagorno-Karabakh itself to back demands that the mountainous
enclave be put under Armenian control.
   Valeri Sidorov, speaking for the Kremlin-appointed commission
now governing the disputed region, said the strikers' demands had
been forwarded to Moscow.
   However, he said local authorities were less worried about the
strikes than about preventing a new outbreak of ethnic violence.
   ``The situation has to be closely watched'' because the
atmosphere is so tense, he said.
   Several days ago, authorities took a harsher tone, warning they
would use ``all available means'' to prevent more unrest.
</TEXT>
