<FIRST>r a AM-RitualSlayings-US 1stLd-Writethru a0716 05-07 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ritual Slayings-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Relieved Drug-Cult Members Arrested In Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Sara Maria ...,' to CORRECT that Aldrete arrested
with four others, sted 3.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ritual Slayings, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. law enforcers expressed relief
Sunday that four suspected members of a drug-smuggling cult that
killed 15 people were arrested in Mexico, not the United States.
   ``They committed the crimes in Mexico,'' said Oran Neck, chief
U.S. Customs agent in this border city at Texas' southern tip. ``If
they commited murder in Mexico, we can't charge them here.''
   Cult leader Adolfo de Jesus Constanzo, 26, and a follower,
Martin Quintana Rodriguez, were killed in Mexico City, authorities
said after a shootout there.
   Sara Maria Aldrete, a former Texas college honor student
described as the ``godmother'' or ``witch'' of the cult, was
arrested at the same Mexico City residence with four others
suspected of belonging to the murderous drug ring.
   Ms. Aldrete, 24, said in Mexico City on Sunday that Constanzo
ordered himself and his right-hand man, Martin Quintana Rodriguez,
killed when police closed in.
   FBI Agent Bob Nixon of Brownsville agreed that it was best that
Ms. Aldrete and the others were arrested in Mexico.
   ``It's great,'' Nixon said. ``It will save us from having to
extradite them'' (to Mexico).
   Constanzo and Ms. Aldrete were among 11 people indicted by a
U.S. federal grand jury in McAllen on drug charges in the case.
   ``The only reason we were looking for them was so we could
extradite them to Mexico so they could be tried there,'' Nixon
said. ``The only purpose of the drug indictments here was to have
probable cause to pick them up and turn them over to Mexico.''
   The task force that handled the case included the FBI, the U.S.
Drug Enforcement Administration, the Customs Service and the
Cameron County Sheriff's Department.
   Cameron County Sheriff Alex Perez said he did not expect U.S.
officials to try to extradite those in custody in Mexico to the
United States.
   ``I hope they stay over there in Mexico, because that's where
the murders were coordinated and they have to stand trial over
there,'' Perez said.
   Under Mexican law, the worst punishment any of the suspects
could receive is 50 years in prison.
   Mexican officials last month located 15 bodies at or near a
ranch west of the border city of Matamoros, Mexico. The dead,
including a U.S. college student, are believed to be the victims of
a cult that performed human sacrifices and mutilations to bring
magical protection to drug smuggling.
   Five men arrested the week the bodies were exhumed have been
indicted on Mexican federal charges, including first-degree murder,
kidnapping, illegal burial, weapons and drug violations and
cover-up.
   Of the 11 indicted in the United States, two are dead, one was
in U.S. custody and six were in Mexican custody Sunday. Two
remained at large.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
