<FIRST>r i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0713 05-07 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Urges Poles To Back Union Candidates</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS five grafs with talks on miners' strike.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLOCK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa on Sunday
told thousands of cheering supporters to take a first step toward a
free Poland by electing union-backed candidates to Parliament next
month.
   After Mass at the Plock cathedral, about 5,000 people walked
down a grassy hill to an open amphitheater overlooking the Vistula
River. There, Walesa introduced the union's five candidates to
represent the region in the Sejm and the Senate.
   Walesa emphasized his roots in the rural central Polish region,
a three-hour drive from his current home in the Baltic port of
Gdansk. He was born in the nearby village of Popowo and told the
crowd he had been baptized in Plock.
   He urged voters to take advantage of new reforms that allow
limited opposition participation in the June 4 legislative
elections for the first time in the history of Communist Poland.
   ``If we stand aside ... someone else will shape this Poland for
us again. So I appeal to you, let's build Poland together,'' he
said.
   ``Our representatives at the Sejm and Senate can create a
platform from which we will jump into freedom and independence. If
we don't do that, our chance to have influenced decisions will be
much smaller,'' Walesa said.
   The Solidarity-led opposition agreed to participate in elections
as part of broad accords reached with authorities April 5. The
agreement resulted in the legalization of the trade union movement
after a seven-year ban.
   It also resulted in the creation of a new legislature, the
Senate, and more-open elections for the existing parliament, the
Sejm.
   Independent candidates can run for 161 seats of the 460-member
Sejm, in which a Communist-led alliance is still guaranteed a
majority. All seats are open to any candidates in the new
100-member Senate, the East bloc's first freely elected legislative
body.
   The two chambers form the National Assembly.
   Stanislaw Stomma, an 81-year-old Warsaw lawyer and Roman
Catholic activist running for the Senate with Solidarity's
endorsement, thanked the crowd for the privilege of running from
their town and said he would spend more time there if he were
elected.
   The law does not require candidates to live in the areas they
seek to represent.
   Walesa's close adviser, Andrzej Celinski, a 39-year-old Warsaw
sociologist and candidate for the Sejm, told the crowd: ``It will
depend on us just how much freedom and justice and Solidarity there
will be in Poland.''
   Three other Solidarity candidates for the Sejm also made short
speeches.
   While union supporters in Plock welcomed Walesa warmly, he drew
some disapproving glances when he drove up to the bishop's
residence in a shiny blue Mercedes.
   ``Don't worry, it's borrowed,'' he said. ``Good thing,'' quipped
a woman in the crowd.
   The opposition rally came during a three-day miners' strike that
has stopped nearly all copper mining in Poland.
   Negotiators resumed talks Sunday in an effort to find a
compromise in the dispute, according to Solidarity Information
Service in Warsaw. It gave no details, however.
   The strike, involving about 20,000 workers, is the country's
first major bout of labor unrest since the opposition and
government reached their accords last month.
   The strike broke out at four mines near the city of Lubin, about
200 miles southwest of Warsaw. The mines represent nearly all of
Poland's copper production, which is an important source of
hard-currency earnings.
   Miners are demanding a 50 percent pay increase, according to Jan
Sugalski, a local Solidarity activist. They now earn $118-176 a
month.
</TEXT>
