<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-Observers 1stLd-writethru a0690 05-07 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Observers, 1st Ld-writethru, a0690,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Observers Differ On Voting Irregularities</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with some observers speaking of voting
irregularities, details. Pickup 5th pvs, `Carter was...' Edits thereafter
to trim.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some foreign observers of Panama's
presidential election said Sunday they saw no evidence of voting
irregularities despite opposition predictions of fraud, but others
were less flattering.
   ``They (the government) tried to put on a nice play, but it
wasn't Shakespeare,'' said Jurgen Koch, a West German observer
invited by Panama's human rights commission.
   Former President Jimmy Carter, invited by the Panamanian
government, appeared satisfied with the voting process. ``The only
problem I've seen is with the number of voters,'' he said,
referring to the long lines of voters as he visited polls at the
Torrijos-Carter Elementary School in the sprawling, dusty,
working-class suburb of San Miguelito.
   He said there had been complaints in some precincts about
ballots arriving late, but ``I've checked with the opposition and
the government representatives at the polls ... and they don't seem
to have any problems at the places where I've been.''
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., part of an univited 13-member
delegation sent by President Bush, said his group had seen
irregularities.
   ``The general belief is that the election will be stolen
sometime tonight,'' McCain said as polls closed at 5 p.m.
   ``We've seen many irregularities but it is difficult to judge
the extent of the irregularities,'' he said.
   The Bush delegation arrived Saturday, apparently traveling under
temporary duty orders from the U.S. Department of Defense.
   The Panamanian government had said the delegation was not
welcome and would not be issued visas. But election officials
allowed the group to visit polling places.
   Koch echoed complaints by pollwatchers from the opposition
Christian Democratic Party that hundreds of voters had been
instructed to go to certain voting stations in precincts known to
favor the opposition, only to get there and be told they were not
registered.
   Panama ``tolerated observers but did not let them get to close
to the action,'' Koch said.
   Carter was greeted in San Miguelito by cheering crowds of voters
who yelled, ``Viva Jimmy!'' and ``We love you very much Jimmy
Carter.''
   The elementary school is named after the 1977 treaties under
which the United States is to hand over the Panama Canal to Panama
at the end of the century. Carter and Omar Torrijos, the late
Panamanian dictator, signed the treaties.
   Carter headed an observer delegation that included former
President Gerald Ford. He visited more than a half dozen voting
places around Panama City.
   Bush delegation leader Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., said he saw no
signs of irregularities but guards had threatened to remove a Costa
Rican observer from polls at one precinct near the capital for
allegedly being too close.
   Murtha said the attempt was shouted down by opposition voters.
   ``People feel very strongly about this election. It is going to
be difficult to have a fraudulent election and overcome what the
polls indicate,'' he said.
   Published polls gave opposition candidate Guillermo Endara a
2-to-1 edge over pro-government candidate Carlos Duque.
   The opposition, while welcoming the observers, predicted the
election would be rigged.
   It said the government issued duplicate voting cards to some
Panamanians, allowing them to vote more than once, and planned a
fraudulent computer vote count.
   Luis Felipe Romero, a Mexican observer invited, like Koch, by
the Panamanian Human Rights Commission, said ``It's all quiet so
far.''
   He and other observers were told by the rights commission to
stay 100 feet or so from the nearest booth to avoid the appearance
of interference.
   Manuel Burgos, an opposition spokesman, claimed that five Costa
Rican observers were detained Saturday night in Chitre province,
interrogated and had their luggage searched. They were released
Sunday morning, he said.
</TEXT>
