<FIRST>r a AM-StrandedCrew     05-07 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stranded Crew,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forty-one People Stranded on Bering Sea Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard was waiting for better
weather Sunday before attempting to rescue 41 people stranded on a
Bering Sea island after their skiff capsized in rough seas.
   Crew members from the crab-processing ship Coastal Star were
stranded on St. Matthew Island after leaving their ship for a
beachcombing trip Friday, Coast Guard spokesman Fritz Richter said.
   The ship, the 320-foot Coastal Star, is anchored an undetermined
distance off St. Matthew Island, which is about 425 miles north of
the Aleutian Islands.
   The 66 crew members stil aboard the ship floated survival suits,
food and radios to the island to held their stranded colleagues
survive their first night.
   On Saturday, a C-130 aircraft dispatched from the Coast Guard
base at Kodiak dropped tents, food, warm clothing, sleeping bags
and fuel to the island, where it was snowing, Richter said.
   ``They are safe for the time being and I think relatively
comfortable,'' he said Sunday. ``They were able to build a fire.''
   As they waited for calmer weather, the Coast Guard cutter
Jarvis' crew patrolled the island's north coast, looking for a
stretch of beach on which to land a flat-bottomed rescue vessel.
   Winds of 45 knots and seas up to 15 feet had prevented vessels
from providing help on Friday and Saturday.
   Richter said he assumed the skiff had been ferrying small groups
of crew members to the island when the craft capsized, tossing an
undetermined number of people into the icy water. But he said the
passengers were close enough to swim to shore, and there were no
reports of injuries or hypothermia.
   The crew members are workers aboard the fish processor.
   ``I have no idea why they would be beachcombing in weather like
this,'' Coast Guard spokesman Greg Robinson said in Juneau.
   The Coastal Star, which can carry 120 people, is based in
Petersburg, Alaska, and owned by Icicle Seafoods of Seattle. No one
answered the telephone at Icicle Seafoods on Sunday.
</TEXT>
