<FIRST>r a AM-JoggerRaped     05-07 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jogger Raped,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardinal O'Connor Visits With Central Park Rape Suspects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John J. O'Connor said Sunday he is
counseling the teen-age suspects in the gang rape of a Central Park
jogger to ease their suffering and has visited the victim and her
family several times.
   ``It was clear that she and her family were suffering so much,''
O'Connor said of the victim and her parents.
   But the Roman Catholic leader said he felt compelled to also
reach out to the suspects' families.
   ``I realized that the families of those boys would be suffering
and I would make myself available to do anything that I could do to
help them,'' O'Connor said outside St. Patrick's Cathedral.
   O'Connor said he wrote the parents of the six youths accused in
the April 19 attack and ``told them that I was available to assist
in any way that I could without entering into the judicial
process.''
   O'Connor said he subsequently met with five of the boys at
Spofford Juvenile Center in the Bronx and with the sixth suspect at
the Rikers Island jail. It was not clear when the visits took place.
   O'Connor said he ``walked away with a great sense of sadness''
after his visit with the boys and described the park attack as a
``complex nightmare.''
   ``Those kids, their lives will have to be changed whatever
happens to them by way of the judicial process and the families,
they must be traumatized,'' he said.
   The victim, a28-year-old Wall Street investment banker, was
attacked while jogging after dark along her usual route in Central
Park. She was beaten, raped and left for dead in a mud puddle, and
spent two weeks in a coma, police said.
   She emerged from a coma last week, and was in critical and
stable condition on Sunday, hospital officials said.
   O'Connor said he deliberately avoided talking about the attack
with the suspects and spoke in general terms to the boys.
   ``I talked the kind of thing that one talks with lads who are
confined under those circumstances,'' O'Connor said. ``Where are
you in school? Where are you in the family? How many kids in your
family?''
   He said the boys were glad to see him and asked him to return.
O'Connor said he planned to meet with some of the boys' parents
sometime this week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
