<FIRST>r a AM-StrandedCrewmen1stLd-Writethru a0   05-07 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stranded Crewmen 1st Ld-Writethru, a0,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forty-one Stranded Crewmen Rescued From Bering Sea Island</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with all 41 sailors rescued, DELETE
now-redundant material; picks up 8th graf, `Winds of ...'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Updates with all rescued
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard on Sunday rescued 41
sailors stranded on a Bering Sea island for two days after their
skiff capsized in rough seas, officials said.
   Crew from the Coast Guard cutter Jarvis used a raft and a small
boat to shuttle the sailors from St. Matthew Island to their crab
processing ship after harsh weather subsided, Coast Guard Lt. Jeff
Merrell.
   All of those rescued were in good condition, Merrell said.
   The crab processing ship, the 320-foot Coastal Star, was
anchored off the island about 425 miles north of the Aleutian
Islands.
   The sailors were stranded on the island Friday after leaving the
ship for a beachcombing trip, Coast Guard spokesman Fritz Richter
said.
   The 66 crew members still aboard the ship floated survival
suits, food and radios to the island to held their stranded
colleagues survive their first night.
   On Saturday, a C-130 aircraft dispatched from the Coast Guard
base at Kodiak dropped tents, food, warm clothing, sleeping bags
and fuel to the island, where it was snowing, Richter said.
   Winds of 45 knots and seas up to 15 feet prevented vessels from
providing help on Friday and Saturday.
   Richter said he assumed the skiff had been ferrying small groups
of crew members to the island when the craft capsized, tossing an
undetermined number of people into the icy water. But he said the
passengers were close enough to swim to shore, and there were no
reports of injuries or hypothermia.
   The crew members are workers aboard the fish processor.
   ``I have no idea why they would be beachcombing in weather like
this,'' Coast Guard spokesman Greg Robinson said in Juneau.
   The Coastal Star, which can carry 120 people, is based in
Petersburg, Alaska, and owned by Icicle Seafoods of Seattle. No one
answered the telephone at Icicle Seafoods on Sunday.
</TEXT>
