<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow in Northeast, Thunderstorms in Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE snowfall in Rochester; picks up
4th graf pvs, `Seven inches ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An out-of-season snowstorm left more than 10 inches of snow on
the ground in western New York state on Sunday, and powerful
thunderstorms caused flash flooding in Texas.
   Low-temperature records were set in more than a dozen cities
from Alabama to Illinois.
   In Rochester, N.Y., 10.1 inches of snow piled up by late Sunday,
shattering that city's record for snowfall by more than 6{ inches.
   Seven inches of snow fell in Batavia and Warsaw, N.Y., and snow
broke tree limbs and downed power lines throughout the western
Finger Lakes.
   The unusual weather was caused by low pressure centered over
extreme south-central Quebec that drew moist, cold air south across
the Ohio Valley and Appalachian Mountains. Snow fell over parts of
New York, Pennsylvania, West Virginia and Ohio.
   By early afternoon, temperatures had risen above freezing over
most of the area and the snow was either mixed with rain or changed
to rain.
   Severe thunderstorms raked parts of north-central Texas with
heavy rains and golf ball-size hail. Graham, Texas, was especially
hard hit. The slow movement of the storms caused some flash
flooding over parts of Young, Jack and Palo Pinto counties.
   Elsewhere, scattered showers lingered from northeast North
Carolina to Maryland and Delaware, and rain and snow were mixed
across northern sections of lower Michigan.
   Pueblo, Colo., recorded a record high temperature for the date
of 79 degrees. But most of the records set Sunday were for low
temperatures.
   Among the record lows were 29 degrees in Champaign, Ill.; 29 in
Chicago; 34 in Fayetteville, Ark.; 38 in Fort Smith, Ark.; 28 in
Fort Wayne, Ind.; 37 in Greer, S.C.; 41 in Huntsville, Ala.; 34 in
Kansas City, Mo.; 29 in Lincoln, Neb.; 36 in Louisville, Ky.; 24 in
Madison, Wis.; 42 in Meridian, Miss.; 35 in Paducah, Ky.; 30 in St.
Joseph, Mo.; 28 in South Bend, Ind.; and 31 in Springfield, Mo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 33
degrees at Johnstown, Pa., to 101 degrees at both Needles, Calif.,
and Yuma, Ariz.
   The nation's low Sunday morning was 22 degrees at Beloit, Wis.
   The forecast for Monday called for showers across New England,
New York state and northern Pennsylvania, with snow showers
possible at higher elevations; scattered showers and thunderstorms
from Oklahoma to the northern Plains and the upper Mississippi
Valley; widely scattered thunderstorms in much of Texas and the
mountains of Wyoming and Colorado; and mostly sunny skies around
the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 50s and 60s from the
northern Plains to the Great Lakes, New England and the Carolinas;
the 90s and above from the central valleys and southern deserts of
California to central and southern Texas; and in the 70s and 80s
elsewhere.
</TEXT>
