<FIRST>r f AM-StateAds     05-07 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-State Ads,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Advertising In Each Other to Draw Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alabama's billboard confronts one of Michigan's
greatest concentrations of influential businesses, catching the eye
like a red flag on the I-94 ``automation alley'' thoroughfare
linking Detroit and Ann Arbor.
   ``Detroit, Start Your Engines. Alabama Is Open For Business,''
it reads.
   The Alabama Development Office, Alabama corporations and
communities help pay for billboards such as that one in cities
ranging from St. Louis to New York, spokesman Robert Sutton said.
   Visits from Alabama emissaries follow in search of more
industries like Huntsville's high technology and computer
companies, Birmingham's medical research facilities and forest
products enterprises statewide, Sutton said.
   Michigan officials try to lure companies and travelers by
advertising in other states too, but they aren't heading for
Alabama _ with banjos, billboards or any other direct counterattack.
   ``We don't do billboards. We've never felt it would necessarily
do the job for us,'' said Al Sandner of the tourist-seeking state
Travel Bureau.
   There will also be no `Bama billboard battle by the state
Manufacturing Development Group, which goes after new offices and
plants, marketing unit director Jeff Mason said.
   ``As opposed to going into a number of different states, we have
targeted particular industries,'' Mason said. ``Then we have
searched out the most rapidly growing industries in those
categories.''
   Mason's department spends $3 million a year on advertising to
lure business to Michigan. Sandner's agency spends $4.5 million to
draw tourists.
   Battling back, neighoring Wisconsin, Illinois, Indiana, Ohio and
Ontario Province in Canada are familiar advertisers for tourists in
Michigan, as well as southerly destinations like Kentucky,
Tennessee, Florida and Texas.
   Michigan spends its tourist ad money on television, magazine,
newspaper supplement and radio ads in many of those same states,
Sandner said. It attracts most of its tourists from the Chicago
area.
   When summer simmers, Alabama, as well as Florida, Georgia,
Mississippi, Louisiana and Arkansas, are ideal targets for magazine
spreads showing rippling waters and golf greens that stay green.
   ``We'll use a four-color photo of some spectacular Great Lakes
scene _ water scenes _ and hint that the water goes on forever. The
subliminal message being when July and August get to be too much in
Central Florida, come on up to our peninsulas and cool off,'' he
said.
   When Michigan wants to bag businesses, it doesn't aim at
neighbors, Mason said.
   ``Our posture has been not to go robbing Peter to pay Paul.
Ultimately you end up redistributing the number of businesses
between the two states and really not increasing the amount of
business activity.
   ``You're just capturing one for the one that left,'' he said.
``We're looking to expand the ones that are here and capture the
ones looking at new locations.''
</TEXT>
