<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern'sEmployees     05-07 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern's Employees,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern, Employees Hang On As Walkout Enters Third Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They know their efforts could be wiped out by the
liquidation of their company or a housecleaning by a new owner, but
a group of Eastern employees is keeping up a skeleton operation at
the strikebound carrier.
   ``It's a risk, but I happen to believe in what we're doing, so
it's a risk you take,'' said Bob Tripp, explaining why he has
stayed with Eastern despite its uncertain future.
   Tripp was mopping floors Friday as the strike by Eastern's
machinists, pilots and flight attendants entered its third month.
The 23-year Eastern employee wearing the grimed workclothes is
normally manager of internal distribution.
   ``This is Management Development 101,'' he said. ``I'm doing all
the things I usually supervise from my white-collar job.''
   With 4,500 employees, down from nearly 30,000 before the strike,
Eastern workers are averaging 10 to 12 hours a day without extra
compensation and most have several sets of duties. The carrier is
flying about 10 percent of its pre-strike schedule.
   Texas Air Corp., which owns Eastern, is hoping a U.S. Bankruptcy
Court judge will approve a plan that provides for the sale of $1.8
billion in assets, leaving a smaller, reorganized carrier staffed
by nonunion workers.
   Eastern's unions say the carrier, which filed for reorganization
under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code after the strike
began, should be sold to one of several prospective buyers who have
until May 10 to submit bids.
   Some independent analysts have said Eastern should be liquidated.
   But the remaining Eastern workers want to see their company pull
through.
   ``Chapter 11 _ It's the First Chapter of the Rest of Your Life''
proclaim posters throughout the carrier's headquarters and its
shops at Miami International Airport.
   ``Eastern Will Survive,'' other signs promise.
   Smaller, handwritten signs taped to bathroom doors remind
employees that there are no paid cleaners anymore, so each employee
must help keep things clean.
   Few people are doing only their normal, prestrike jobs.
   Bob Wolf, the domestic advertising manager, was in overalls
Friday, working in the wheels and brakes department. He also helps
pack the liquor kits for flights.
   Nearby, two computer programmers were repairing plane tires.
   Cira Tellechea, an area sales manager, was welding an aluminum
patch onto a plane part.
   On Friday, Eastern averaged 71 passengers on its 110 or so daily
flights _ less than one-third capacity for many of its planes.
   But the airline's remaining workers point to stellar on-time
rates of 96.5 percent and reduced complaints about lost bags and
other passenger problems.
   ``It's a piece of cake, no sweat at all,'' said Leo Ouellette, a
supervisor at Systems Control, where dispatchers monitor the
locations of all of Eastern's planes and crews. ``With 110 flights
a day when we're used to 1,000 or more, things are very efficient.''
   Eastern is getting ready to add more flights, with 264 new
pilots in training and interviews scheduled with 270 more this
week. The company took out newspapers ads Sunday to hire new
mechanics, and the first new flight attendants began training last
week and schools for 56 each in Miami and Atlanta will probably
begin this week.
</TEXT>
